<tr>
<td rowspan="1" colspan="2" width="NaN" valign="centre">


<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Mr.&nbsp;Scott was Walmart&rsquo;s President and CEO from January&nbsp;2000 through his retirement from that position on January&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2009. Mr.&nbsp;Scott served as an Executive Officer of Walmart and as the Chairman of the Executive Committee of the Board until January&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2011, when he retired from our company. Prior to serving as President and CEO of Walmart, he held other positions with Walmart since joining our company in September&nbsp;1979, including Vice Chairman and Chief Operating Officer from January&nbsp;1999 to January&nbsp;2000, and Executive Vice President and President and CEO, Walmart U.S. from January&nbsp;1998 to January&nbsp;1999. Mr.&nbsp;Scott served as a director of The Goldman Sachs Group,&nbsp;Inc. from May&nbsp;2010 to May&nbsp;2011. Mr.&nbsp;Scott serves as a director of several privately-held companies and on the advisory board of the Tsinghua University School of Economics and Management in Beijing, China. He has been a member of the Board since 1999. </p>

<p style="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:12pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; font-style:italic; color: #007DC3">Skills and Qualifications: </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Mr.&nbsp;Scott&rsquo;s qualifications to serve on the Board include his extensive knowledge of the global retail industry gained through his more than 30 years of leadership experience at Walmart, including nine years as our company&rsquo;s CEO, as well as his in-depth knowledge of our company, expertise in corporate strategy, and organizational acumen. In addition, through his service on the Board and his service on other boards of directors, Mr.&nbsp;Scott provides considerable operational, strategic planning, and leadership experience to the Board.</p>

</td>
</tr>

Mr.&nbsp;Walton also serves as Chairman of Community Publishers,&nbsp;Inc., which operates newspapers in Arkansas, Missouri, and Oklahoma. Mr.&nbsp;Walton also brings to the Board his executive leadership, strategic planning, and management experience gained through his leadership positions at the companies described above, as well as his knowledge of our company and its operations gained through his service on the Board and the SPFC.</p>

</td><td rowspan="1" colspan="1" width="876.5118110236224" style="padding-right:0pt;vertical-align:middle;" valign="">

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">

<b>Joined the Board:</b> 1978 </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">

<b>Age:</b> 68 </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">

<b>Board Committees:</b> Executive Committee; Global Compensation Committee </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">

<b>Other Current Public Company Directorships</b>: None </p>

</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td rowspan="1" colspan="2" width="NaN" valign="centre">

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Mr.&nbsp;Walton is the Chairman of Walmart and has been a member of the Board since 1978. He joined our company in 1969 and, prior to becoming Chairman in 1992, held a variety of positions with our company, including Senior Vice President, Corporate Secretary, General Counsel, and Vice Chairman. Before joining Walmart, Mr.&nbsp;Walton was in private law practice as a partner with the law firm of Conner&nbsp;&amp; Winters in Tulsa, Oklahoma. In addition to his duties at Walmart, Mr.&nbsp;Walton is involved with a number of non-profit and educational organizations, including Conservation International, where he serves as Chairman of that organization&rsquo;s executive committee, and the College of Wooster, where he is an Emeritus Life Trustee for the college. </p>

<p style="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:12pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; font-style:italic; color: #007DC3">Skills and Qualifications: </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Mr.&nbsp;Walton&rsquo;s qualifications to serve on the Board include his decades of leadership experience with Walmart, as well as his in-depth knowledge of our company, its history and the retail industry, all gained through 35 years of service on the Board and more than 20 years of service as our company&rsquo;s Chairman. The Board also benefits from Mr.&nbsp;Walton&rsquo;s expertise in corporate governance and strategic planning gained through his service on the boards and other governing entities of numerous non-profit organizations, as well as his legal and corporate governance expertise gained as Walmart&rsquo;s Corporate Secretary and General Counsel and as an attorney in private practice.</p>

</td>
</tr>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">

<b>Age:</b> 55 </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">

<b>Board Committees:</b> Audit Committee; Executive Committee </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">

<b>Other Current Public Company Directorships: </b>Caesars Entertainment Corporation<b></b>

</p>
<b></b>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td rowspan="1" colspan="2" width="NaN" valign="centre">

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Mr.&nbsp;Williams is the Chairman and CEO of The Williams Capital Group, L.P., an investment bank. Since 2003, he has also served as the Chairman and CEO of Williams Capital Management, LLC, an investment management firm. Mr.&nbsp;Williams also serves as a trustee of the Williams Capital Management Trust, a registered investment company. He has served as a director of Caesars Entertainment Corporation (formerly Harrah&rsquo;s Entertainment,&nbsp;Inc.) from November&nbsp;2003 to January&nbsp;2008, and from April&nbsp;2008 to the present. He has also served on the board of directors of Cox Enterprises,&nbsp;Inc. since 2012 and is a member of the boards of several educational institutions and non-profit organizations, including the Lincoln Center for the Performing Arts and the Tuck School of Business at Dartmouth College. Mr.&nbsp;Williams has been a member of the Board since 2004. </p>

<p style="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:12pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; font-style:italic; color: #007DC3">Skills and Qualifications: </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Mr.&nbsp;Williams&rsquo; qualifications to serve on the Board include his experience and expertise in investment banking and corporate finance gained through his years in the investment banking industry. The Board also benefits from Mr.&nbsp;Williams&rsquo; executive management and leadership experience as the Chairman and CEO of an investment bank and investment management firm. In addition, through his service on various public company and non-profit boards, including his service on the Board and the Audit Committee, Mr.&nbsp;Williams brings diverse and valuable financial, accounting, management and strategic expertise to the Board.</p>

</td>
</tr>

<font color="#007DC3">Linda S. Wolf</font>

<p style="margin-top:1pt; margin-left:8pt; margin-bottom:25pt; border-top:1pt solid #007DC3; line-height:20pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:28pt; font-weight:bold"></p>

</td><td rowspan="1" colspan="1" width="876.5118110236224" style="padding-right:0pt;vertical-align:middle;" valign="">
<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">

<b>Joined the Board:</b> 2005 </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">

<b>Age:</b> 65 </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">

<b>Board Committees:</b> CNGC; TeCC </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">

<b>Other Current Public Company Directorships:</b> Innerworkings,&nbsp;Inc.</p>

<tr>
<td rowspan="1" colspan="2" width="NaN" valign="centre">

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Ms.&nbsp;Wolf is the former Chairman and CEO of Leo Burnett Worldwide,&nbsp;Inc. (&ldquo;Leo Burnett&rdquo;), a global advertising agency and division of Publicis Groupe S.A. Ms.&nbsp;Wolf served in various positions with Leo Burnett and its predecessors from 1978 to April&nbsp;2005, including as Chairman and CEO from January&nbsp;2001 until April&nbsp;2005. She serves as a trustee for investment funds advised by the Janus Capital Group Inc. and has served on the board of InnerWorkings,&nbsp;Inc., a provider of managed print and promotional procurement solutions, since November&nbsp;2006, and Wrapports, LLC since 2012. Among other endeavors, Ms.&nbsp;Wolf serves on the boards of the Field Museum, Children&rsquo;s Memorial Hospital, and The Chicago Council on Global Affairs. Ms.&nbsp;Wolf has been a member of the Board since 2005. </p>

<p style="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:12pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; font-style:italic; color: #007DC3">Skills and Qualifications: </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Ms.&nbsp;Wolf&rsquo;s qualifications to serve on the Board include her brand management and marketing experience gained through her years at Leo Burnett. The Board also benefits from her executive leadership and management experience gained as a CEO. Ms.&nbsp;Wolf, through her service on a variety of public company and non-profit boards, including her service on the Board and the CNGC, also provides considerable governance, operational, investment, and strategic planning acumen to the Board.</p>


</td>
</tr>

</i></font>
</p>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:3pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:20pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold ">Are there any directors not standing for reelection? </p>
<p style="margin-top:1pt; margin-left:8pt; margin-bottom:25pt; border-top:1pt solid #007DC3; line-height:20pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:28pt; font-weight:bold"></p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Yes. James W. Breyer, M. Michele Burns, and Arne M. Sorenson, each of whom currently serve on the Board, will rotate off the Board at the conclusion of their current term in accordance with our Corporate Governance Guidelines and will not stand for reelection at the 2013 Annual Shareholders&rsquo; Meeting. Mr.&nbsp;Breyer and Ms.&nbsp;Burns have each served on the Board for more than a decade, and Mr.&nbsp;Sorenson is departing the Board after five years of service to focus on his increased responsibilities as President and CEO of Marriott International,&nbsp;Inc. Included below is information regarding each of Mr.&nbsp;Breyer&rsquo;s, Ms.&nbsp;Burns&rsquo;, and Mr.&nbsp;Sorenson&rsquo;s specific experience, qualifications, attributes, and skills that led the Board to conclude that he or she should serve as a director. </p>

<p style="margin-top:16pt; margin-bottom:1pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:12pt; font-family:Arial; font-weight:bold; font-size:12pt;" align="justify">
<font><i>


<table style="margin-top:3pt; margin-bottom:12pt; border:1.5pt solid #007DC3; padding-left: 8.5pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt;" cellspacing="0" align="center" width="100%" cellpadding="5" frame="void">
<tr>
<td rowspan="1" colspan="2" width="NaN" valign="centre">
<a name="_N10EC5"></a>

<font color="#007DC3">James W. Breyer</font>

</p>
<p style="margin-top:1pt; margin-left:8pt; margin-bottom:25pt; border-top:1pt solid #007DC3; line-height:20pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:28pt; font-weight:bold"></p>

</td>
</tr>

<td rowspan="1" colspan="1" width="144.85196850393686" style="padding-right:0pt;vertical-align:bottom;" valign="">

</td><td rowspan="1" colspan="1" width="876.5118110236224" style="padding-right:0pt;vertical-align:middle;" valign="">

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">

<b>Joined the Board:</b> 2001 </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">

<b>Age:</b> 51 </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">

<b>Board Committees:</b> SPFC; TeCC </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">

<b>Other Current Public Company Directorships:</b> Dell,&nbsp;Inc.; Facebook,&nbsp;Inc.; News Corporation; Model N,&nbsp;Inc.</p>

</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td rowspan="1" colspan="2" width="NaN" valign="centre">


<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Mr.&nbsp;Breyer has been a Partner of Accel Partners, a venture capital firm, since 1987. Mr.&nbsp;Breyer is also the founder and has been the Chief Executive Officer of Breyer Capital, an investment firm, since July&nbsp;2006. Mr.&nbsp;Breyer is also a co-founder and has been co-lead on the strategic investment committee since inception of the IDG-Accel China Funds. In addition to serving on our Board, Mr.&nbsp;Breyer currently serves as a member of the boards of directors of Dell,&nbsp;Inc., Facebook,&nbsp;Inc., News Corporation, and Model N,&nbsp;Inc.. Mr.&nbsp;Breyer previously served as a member of the board of directors of Brightcove Inc. from January&nbsp;2007 to January&nbsp;2013, Marvel Entertainment Inc. from June&nbsp;2006 to December&nbsp;2009, Prosper Marketplace Inc. from April&nbsp;2005 to June&nbsp;2012, and RealNetworks,&nbsp;Inc. from October&nbsp;1995 to June&nbsp;2008. Mr.&nbsp;Breyer holds a B.S. in interdisciplinary studies from Stanford University and an M.B.A. from Harvard University. Mr.&nbsp;Breyer has been a member of the Board since 2001. </p>

<p style="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:12pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; font-style:italic; color: #007DC3">Skills and Qualifications: </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Mr.&nbsp;Breyer&rsquo;s qualifications to serve on the Board include his experience gained through his venture capital activities, including his partnership in Accel Partners, through which he brings to the Board insight into strategic planning, investment expertise, and entrepreneurship. The Board also benefits from Mr.&nbsp;Breyer&rsquo;s extensive knowledge of the technology industry and insight into existing and emerging technologies relevant to Walmart&rsquo;s business. In addition, through his years of service on the boards of public and private companies and other organizations, including his service on the Board and the SPFC, Mr.&nbsp;Breyer provides the Board with diverse and valuable financial, operational, and leadership expertise.</p>

<tr>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Ms.&nbsp;Burns is the Chief Executive Officer of the Retirement Policy Center sponsored by Marsh&nbsp;&amp; McLennan Companies,&nbsp;Inc. (&ldquo;MMC&rdquo;), a global professional services and consulting firm, a position she has held since October&nbsp;2011. Prior to that role, Ms.&nbsp;Burns was the Chairman and CEO of Mercer Inc. (&ldquo;Mercer&rdquo;), a subsidiary of MMC, from September&nbsp;2006 until October&nbsp;2011. She joined MMC in March&nbsp;2006 and served as its Executive Vice President and CFO until September&nbsp;2006. She is the former Executive Vice President, CFO, and Chief Restructuring Officer of Mirant Corporation, an energy company, where she served from May&nbsp;2004 to January&nbsp;2006. She served as the Executive Vice President and CFO of Delta Air Lines,&nbsp;Inc. (&ldquo;Delta&rdquo;), an air carrier, from August&nbsp;2000 through April&nbsp;2004. Prior to joining Delta, Ms.&nbsp;Burns was a partner at Arthur Andersen LLP. She has also served as a director of The Goldman Sachs Group,&nbsp;Inc. since October&nbsp;2011 and Cisco Systems,&nbsp;Inc. since 2003. Ms.&nbsp;Burns has been a member of the Board since 2003. </p>

<p style="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:12pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; font-style:italic; color: #007DC3">Skills and Qualifications: </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">As the Chief Financial Officer of several global public companies, Ms.&nbsp;Burns brings to the Board substantial experience in accounting and the review and preparation of financial statements. In addition, as the former Chief Executive Officer of Mercer, Ms.&nbsp;Burns brings to our Board her experience in human capital management and strategic consulting, which assists our Board in its oversight of our company&rsquo;s strategy. Through her service on the boards of directors and board committees of other public companies and not-for-profit entities, Ms.&nbsp;Burns has developed additional leadership and corporate governance expertise.</p>

<font color="#007DC3">Arne M. Sorenson</font>

</p>
<p style="margin-top:1pt; margin-left:8pt; margin-bottom:25pt; border-top:1pt solid #007DC3; line-height:20pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:28pt; font-weight:bold"></p>

</p>

</td><td rowspan="1" colspan="1" width="876.5118110236224" style="padding-right:0pt;vertical-align:middle;" valign="">
<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">

<b>Joined the Board:</b> 2008 </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">

<b>Age: </b>54 </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">

<b>Board Committee:</b> Audit Committee </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">

<b>Other Current Public Company Directorships:</b> Marriott International,&nbsp;Inc.</p>

<tr>
<td rowspan="1" colspan="2" width="NaN" valign="centre">

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Mr.&nbsp;Sorenson is the President and Chief Executive Officer of Marriott International,&nbsp;Inc. (&ldquo;Marriott&rdquo;). Previously, Mr.&nbsp;Sorenson was President and Chief Operating Officer of Marriott from May&nbsp;2009 to March&nbsp;2012, and has served as a member of the Marriott board of directors since February&nbsp;2011. Mr.&nbsp;Sorenson served as Marriott&rsquo;s Executive Vice President and CFO from 1998 to 2009. He also previously held the additional title of Marriott&rsquo;s President, Continental European Lodging, in which capacity he was responsible for lodging operations and development in the continental European region. Mr.&nbsp;Sorenson joined Marriott in 1996 as Senior Vice President of Business Development. He also co-chairs Marriott&rsquo;s Green Council, whose mission is to integrate environmental sustainability into Marriott&rsquo;s business strategy. Prior to joining Marriott, he was a partner in the law firm of Latham&nbsp;&amp; Watkins in Washington, D.C. Mr.&nbsp;Sorenson also serves as a member of the Board of Regents of Luther College. He has been a member of the Board since 2008. </p>

<p style="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:12pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; font-style:italic; color: #007DC3">Skills and Qualifications: </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Mr.&nbsp;Sorenson&rsquo;s qualifications to serve on the Board include his expertise in executive management, strategic planning, and sustainability gained as a senior executive and director of a global corporation. Mr.&nbsp;Sorenson also brings to the Board his expertise in corporate finance, financial reporting, and accounting gained as the CFO of a large public company. The Board also benefits from Mr.&nbsp;Sorenson&rsquo;s legal and transactional experience as a corporate lawyer, as well as his knowledge of our company and its operations gained through his service on the Board and the Audit Committee.</p>

<a name="_N10F4C"></a>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:20pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:28pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:22pt; font-weight:bold">


<font color="#007DC3">Compensation of the Directors</font>


</p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">As described below, the base compensation for Non-Management Directors upon their election to the Board on June&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2012 consisted of a Share award and an annual retainer. During fiscal 2013, Michael T. Duke and S. Robson Walton received compensation only for their services as Executive Officers of our company and not in their capacities as directors. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">For service on the Board for the term beginning upon election at the 2012 Annual Shareholders&rsquo; Meeting on June&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2012, each Non-Management Director received an annual equity award of Shares with a market value of $175,000, rounded to the nearest whole share. These Shares were awarded on June&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2012. The number of Shares awarded was determined by dividing the dollar amount of the award by the closing price of the Shares on the NYSE on the date of the grant. This annual equity award was paid directly in Shares or deferred in stock units, as elected by each Non-Management Director. In addition, each Non-Management Director elected to the Board at the 2012 Annual Shareholders&rsquo; Meeting was entitled to receive an annual retainer of $60,000, payable in arrears in equal quarterly installments for the Board term that commenced upon election at the 2012 Annual Shareholders&rsquo; Meeting. This annual retainer could be received in the form of cash, in Shares (determined by dividing the dollar amount of the quarterly installment by the closing price of the Shares on the NYSE on the payment date of the quarterly installment) rounded to the nearest whole share, deferred in stock units, or deferred into an interest-credited account, as elected by each Non-Management Director. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">The Non-Management Directors who serve as the chair of a Board committee receive an additional retainer for the additional time required for Board committee business. For the Board term commencing on the date of the 2012 Annual Shareholders&rsquo; Meeting, the retainer for the chairs of the Audit Committee and CNGC was $25,000, and the retainer for the chairs of the SPFC and TeCC was $20,000. In addition, Non-Management Directors who serve on more than one standing Board committee receive an additional $15,000 annually. Further, the director appointed by the Board to serve as the presiding director of executive sessions of the Non-Management Directors and Independent Directors receives an additional $20,000 annually. These additional fees are payable in arrears in equal quarterly installments, and as noted above, may be taken in cash, in Shares (determined by dividing the dollar value of the amount of the additional fees by the closing price of the Shares on the NYSE on the payment date of the quarterly installment to such directors) rounded to the nearest whole share, deferred in stock units, or deferred into an interest-credited account, as elected by each Non-Management Director. Finally, each Non-Management Director who attends in person a Board meeting held at a location that requires intercontinental travel from his or her residence is paid a $4,000 meeting attendance fee. This additional fee is intended to compensate our Non-Management Directors for the additional time required to travel intercontinentally, and may be taken in any of the forms described in the preceding sentence, as elected by each Non-Management Director.  </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Since November&nbsp;2011, the Audit Committee has been conducting an internal investigation into, among other things, alleged violations of the U.S. Foreign Corrupt Practices Act of 1977 (the &ldquo;FCPA&rdquo;) and other alleged crimes or misconduct in connection with foreign subsidiaries, including Wal-Mart de M&eacute;xico, S.A.B. de C.V. (&ldquo;Walmex&rdquo;), and whether prior allegations of such violations and/or misconduct were appropriately handled by Walmart. The Audit Committee and Walmart have engaged outside counsel from a number of law firms and other advisors who are assisting in the on-going investigation of these matters. This investigation resulted in a significant increase in the workload of the Audit Committee members during fiscal 2013, and during fiscal 2013, the Audit Committee conducted seven additional meetings related to the investigation, and Audit Committee members received frequent updates via conference calls and other means of communication with outside counsel and other advisors related to the investigation. In November&nbsp;2012, the CNGC and the Board approved an additional fee in the amount of $60,000 payable to each Audit Committee member other than the Audit Committee Chair, and an additional fee in the amount of $85,000 payable to the Audit Committee Chair. These additional fees were determined by calculating the number of hours worked by the Audit Committee members during the regularly scheduled meetings as well as the additional hours required of the committee members due to the investigation. It was determined that during fiscal 2013 the Audit Committee spent approximately twice the amount of time normally required for standard Audit Committee functions. Therefore, the decision was made to double the cash portion of the annual retainer for each Audit Committee member as well as to double the Audit Committee Chair fee for the chair of the Audit Committee. The CNGC and Board approved this additional fee in light of the significant additional time and effort required of the Audit Committee members related to the investigation. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">The Board has adopted stock ownership guidelines for the Non-Management Directors. Each Non-Management Director must own, within five years of his or her initial election or appointment to the Board, an amount of Shares, restricted stock, or stock units having a value equal to five times the annual retainer component of the Non-Management Director&rsquo;s compensation approved by the Board in the year the director was initially elected or appointed. All Non-Management Directors who have reached the five-year compliance date own Shares having a value greater than five times the annual retainer component. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Pursuant to the CNGC&rsquo;s charter, director compensation for the Non-Management Directors is reviewed at least annually by the CNGC, which recommends to the Board the annual compensation for those directors. The compensation paid to the directors during fiscal 2013 is described in the table below. </p>

<p style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 3pt; padding-left: 17.2pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;" align="justify"></p>
<p style="margin:0pt; margin-top:14pt; margin-bottom: 14pt; line-height:10pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt;" align="right">
<img src="footer_walmart.jpg" style="margin-bottom:-5pt;">&nbsp;&nbsp;<i>2013 Proxy Statement</i>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;26</p>

Michael T. Duke and S. Robson Walton are omitted from this table because they received compensation only as Executive Officers of our company during fiscal 2013 and did not receive any additional compensation for their duties as directors. The compensation for Mr.&nbsp;Duke for fiscal 2013 is disclosed in the Summary Compensation table on page&nbsp;55. Mr.&nbsp;Walton&rsquo;s annual salary as Chairman of Walmart is equal to the amount of the annual stock and cash retainer paid to Non-Management Directors, and is therefore $235,000. During fiscal 2013, our company also paid health insurance premiums and made 401(k) Plan contributions for Mr.&nbsp;Duke and Mr.&nbsp;Walton on the same basis as for other Associates. Mr.&nbsp;Duke and Mr.&nbsp;Walton are also eligible to participate in our company&rsquo;s other benefit plans, such as our medical insurance plan and Stock Purchase Plan, on the same basis as all other Associates. </p>

<table style="margin-top:3pt; margin-bottom:12pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt;" cellspacing="0" align="center" width="100%" cellpadding="2" frame="void">
<tr>
<td rowspan="1" colspan="1" width="1023.3637795275588" style="vertical-align:text-top; " valign="top">

<p align="justify" style="margin: 0pt; margin-bottom:-11.5pt; line-height:11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-style: normal; font-size: 9pt;">(3)	</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin: 0pt; margin-bottom:2.5pt; padding-left: 20pt; line-height:11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-style: normal; font-size: 9pt;">Each Non-Management Director elected to the Board at the 2012 Annual Shareholders&rsquo; Meeting received a stock award of 2,670 Shares on June&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2012. The number of Shares was determined by dividing $175,000 by $65.55, which was the closing price of a Share on the NYSE on the grant date, rounded to the nearest whole share. Upon his appointment to the Board on July&nbsp;27,&nbsp;2012, Mr.&nbsp;Flynn received a stock award of 1,988 shares. The number of Shares was determined by dividing $148,151 (a prorated portion of the $175,000 annual stock award value) by $74.52, which was the closing price of a Share on the NYSE on the grant date, rounded to the nearest whole share. Dr.&nbsp;Cash, Mr.&nbsp;Daft, Mr.&nbsp;Flynn, Ms.&nbsp;Mayer, Mr.&nbsp;Penner, Mr.&nbsp;Scott, Mr.&nbsp;Jim C. Walton, and Ms.&nbsp;Wolf deferred the receipt of these Shares until a later date. No current Non-Management Directors held options to purchase Shares as of the end of fiscal 2013. Options held by Mr.&nbsp;Duke at the end of fiscal 2013 are disclosed in the Outstanding Equity Awards at Fiscal 2013 Year-End table below. The options held by Mr.&nbsp;Duke were granted to him in prior years as part of his compensation for service as an Executive Officer of Walmart and not as compensation for serving as a director of our company. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin: 0pt; margin-bottom:-11.5pt; line-height:11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-style: normal; font-size: 9pt;">(4)	</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin: 0pt; margin-bottom:2.5pt; padding-left: 20pt; line-height:11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-style: normal; font-size: 9pt;">The amounts in this column represent above-market interest earned on director compensation deferred to an interest-credited account under the Director Compensation Deferral Plan, as elected by the director. The interest rate on the interest-bearing account is set by the Director Compensation Deferral Plan based on the ten-year United&nbsp;States Treasury note rate on the first day of January&nbsp;plus 2.70&nbsp;percent. This rate was 4.67&nbsp;percent for the calendar year ended December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2012, and decreased to 4.56&nbsp;percent for the calendar year ending December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2013. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin: 0pt; margin-bottom:-11.5pt; line-height:11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-style: normal; font-size: 9pt;">(5)	</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin: 0pt; margin-bottom:2.5pt; padding-left: 20pt; line-height:11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-style: normal; font-size: 9pt;">The amounts in this column include tax gross-ups paid for fiscal 2013 relating to income attributable to spousal travel expenses, meals, and related activities in connection with certain Board meetings during fiscal 2013. For the following directors, this column also includes the aggregate cost of such spousal travel expenses, meals, and related activities in the following amounts:</p>

</td>

<a name="_N113E4"></a>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:20pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:28pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:22pt; font-weight:bold">


<font color="#007DC3">Director Independence</font>


</p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">
A majority of our directors must be independent in accordance with the independence requirements set forth in the NYSE Listed Company Rules. In addition, the Audit Committee and the CNGC must be composed solely of independent directors to comply with the NYSE Listed Company Rules and the SEC&rsquo;s rules. The NYSE Listed Company Rules define specific relationships that disqualify directors from being independent and further require that for a director to qualify as independent, the Board must affirmatively determine that the director has no material relationship with our company. The SEC&rsquo;s rules provide separate definitions of independence for members of audit committees and compensation committees. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">The Board has determined that the following directors are Independent Directors under the independence standards set forth in the NYSE Listed Company Rules: Aida M. Alvarez, James W. Breyer, M. Michele Burns, James I. Cash, Jr., Roger C. Corbett, Douglas N. Daft, Timothy P. Flynn, Marissa A. Mayer, Steven S Reinemund, Arne M. Sorenson, Christopher J. Williams, and Linda S. Wolf. The Board has also determined that the currently serving members of the Audit Committee and the CNGC meet the independence standards for membership on those Board committees set forth in the NYSE Listed Company Rules and the SEC&rsquo;s rules. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">In making these determinations, the Board found that the current Independent Directors do not currently have a material or other disqualifying relationship with Walmart and that the currently serving Independent Directors have not had during the last three years: (i)&nbsp;any of the disqualifying relationships set forth in the NYSE Listed Company Rules referred to above; or (ii)&nbsp;any other material relationship with our company that would compromise his or her independence. The CNGC recommended that the Board make these determinations. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">In April&nbsp;2013, the Board and the CNGC reviewed directors&rsquo; responses to a questionnaire asking about their relationships with the company (and their immediate family members&rsquo; relationships with the company) and other potential conflicts of interest, as well as material provided by management related to transactions, relationships, or arrangements between the company and the directors or parties related to the directors. The Board made its determination as to whether any relationship between a director and Walmart is a material relationship based on the facts and circumstances of the relationship, the amounts involved in the relationship, the director&rsquo;s interest in such relationship, if any, and such other factors as the Board, in its judgment, deemed appropriate. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">In making its determination as to the independence of our Independent Directors, the Board considered certain types of relationships as noted below: </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">the Walmart director was an officer of a Walmart vendor or service provider: Mr.&nbsp;Sorenson and Ms.&nbsp;Mayer; </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">the Walmart director was also a director or trustee of a Walmart vendor or service provider: Mr.&nbsp;Breyer, Dr.&nbsp;Cash, Mr.&nbsp;Daft, Mr.&nbsp;Flynn, Ms.&nbsp;Mayer, Mr.&nbsp;Reinemund, Mr.&nbsp;Sorenson, and Mr.&nbsp;Williams; </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">the Walmart director held, directly or indirectly, more than a 1&nbsp;percent equity interest in a Walmart vendor or service provider: Mr.&nbsp;Breyer; </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">the Walmart director was the member of a board of trustees or advisory board of or held a position in a not-for-profit institution, entity, association or organization to which Walmart made or committed to make donations: Ms.&nbsp;Alvarez, Mr.&nbsp;Breyer, and Mr.&nbsp;Reinemund; and </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">immediate family members of the Walmart director are employed by Walmart vendors or service providers: Ms.&nbsp;Alvarez and Mr.&nbsp;Reinemund. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Certain of these relationships are further described under &ldquo;Related Person Transactions&rdquo; on page 38.  In addition, in making their independence determinations, the Board and the CNGC considered that each of the directors, entities with which she or he is affiliated, or one or more members of her or his immediate family, have in the past purchased property or services from Walmart in retail transactions, all of which transactions were on terms no better than those generally available to Associates at the time of the transactions. All of the other relationships and transactions of the types described above were entered into at arm&rsquo;s length in the normal course of business and, to the extent they are commercial relationships, have standard commercial terms.   </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">In their determination as to Mr.&nbsp;Breyer&rsquo;s independence, the Board and the CNGC considered that, as a partner in Accel Partners and his position at certain related entities (the &ldquo;Accel Funds&rdquo;), Mr.&nbsp;Breyer may be deemed to have an indirect interest in certain companies that engaged in transactions with Walmart in fiscal 2013. In particular, the Board and the CNGC considered Mr.&nbsp;Breyer&rsquo;s interest in Facebook,&nbsp;Inc. (&ldquo;Facebook&rdquo;). As a result of his relationships with certain Accel Funds, Mr.&nbsp;Breyer was attributed beneficial ownership of approximately 11.2% of Facebook prior to May&nbsp;22,&nbsp;2012, the date on which Facebook&rsquo;s initial public offering was consummated, and approximately 1.3% of Facebook immediately after the consummation of that offering. Mr.&nbsp;Breyer&rsquo;s beneficial ownership of Facebook has decreased significantly since May&nbsp;22,&nbsp;2012. At no time has Mr.&nbsp;Breyer&rsquo;s aggregate direct and indirect economic interests in Facebook stock been 5% or more of the total economic interests in Facebook. Mr.&nbsp;Breyer also serves as a member of the board of directors of Facebook. In fiscal 2013, Walmart paid Facebook for display advertising in amounts that represent less than 1% of Facebook&rsquo;s 2012 revenues. Walmart anticipates that it will continue to purchase advertising from Facebook during fiscal 2013. Mr.&nbsp;Breyer has not been and is not currently involved in any transaction between Walmart and Facebook. Based on the Board&rsquo;s consideration of Mr.&nbsp;Breyer&rsquo;s direct ownership of Facebook stock, the Board&rsquo;s understanding of Mr.&nbsp;Breyer&rsquo;s indirect interest in Facebook through the Accel Funds, and the fact that Mr.&nbsp;Breyer is not involved in any transaction between Walmart and Facebook, the Board determined that Mr.&nbsp;Breyer&rsquo;s interest in Facebook does not give rise to a material relationship with Walmart that would impair Mr.&nbsp;Breyer&rsquo;s independence. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">In their determination of Ms.&nbsp;Mayer&rsquo;s independence, the Board and the CNGC considered Ms.&nbsp;Mayer&rsquo;s position as an officer of Google,&nbsp;Inc. (&ldquo;Google&rdquo;) through July&nbsp;17,&nbsp;2012. During fiscal 2013, Walmart paid Google for advertising space on Google&rsquo;s websites and those payments represented less than 1% of Google&rsquo;s 2012 revenues. Walmart anticipates that it will purchase advertising space on Google&rsquo;s websites during fiscal 2014. Ms.&nbsp;Mayer was not involved in any transaction between Walmart and Google. Based on the Board&rsquo;s consideration of Ms.&nbsp;Mayer&rsquo;s position as an officer of Google for a portion of fiscal 2013, the fact that Ms.&nbsp;Mayer was not involved in any transaction between Walmart and Google, and other factors mentioned above, the Board determined that Ms.&nbsp;Mayer&rsquo;s interest in Google did not give rise to a material relationship that would impair Ms.&nbsp;Mayer&rsquo;s independence. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">In their determination of Ms.&nbsp;Alvarez&rsquo;s independence, the Board and the CNGC considered Ms.&nbsp;Alvarez&rsquo;s husband&rsquo;s position as an officer of Kaiser Permanente (&ldquo;Kaiser&rdquo;). In fiscal 2013, Walmart paid Kaiser for health insurance benefits in amounts representing less than 1% of Kaiser&rsquo;s 2012 revenues. Walmart anticipates that it will continue to make payments to Kaiser for health insurance benefits during fiscal 2014. Ms.&nbsp;Alvarez&rsquo;s husband has not been and is not currently involved in any transaction between Walmart and Kaiser. Based on the Board&rsquo;s consideration of Ms.&nbsp;Alvarez&rsquo;s husband&rsquo;s position as an officer of Kaiser, the fact that he is not involved in any transaction between Walmart and Kaiser, and certain other factors mentioned above, the Board determined that Ms.&nbsp;Alvarez&rsquo;s husband&rsquo;s interest in Kaiser does not give rise to a material relationship with Walmart that would impair Ms.&nbsp;Alvarez&rsquo;s independence. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">The Board and the CNGC concluded that none of the above relationships or transactions (including all transactions disclosed under &ldquo;Related Person Transactions&rdquo; on page 38): (i)&nbsp;constitute disqualifying relationships under the NYSE Listed Company Rules; (ii)&nbsp;otherwise compromise the independence of the named directors; or (iii)&nbsp;otherwise constitute a material relationship between Walmart and the directors. </p>

<p style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 3pt; padding-left: 17.2pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;" align="justify"></p>
<p style="margin:0pt; margin-top:14pt; margin-bottom: 14pt; line-height:10pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt;" align="right">
<img src="footer_walmart.jpg" style="margin-bottom:-5pt;">&nbsp;&nbsp;<i>2013 Proxy Statement</i>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;28</p>

</p>

<a name="_N1140B"></a>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:20pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:28pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:22pt; font-weight:bold">


<font color="#007DC3">Board Meetings</font>


</p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">The Board held a total of six meetings during fiscal 2013 to review significant developments affecting our company, engage in strategic planning, and act on matters requiring Board approval. During fiscal 2013, each director attended at least 88 percent of the aggregate number of Board meetings and meetings of Board committees on which he or she served. As a whole, during fiscal 2013, our directors attended approximately 97 percent of the aggregate number of Board meetings and meetings of Board committees on which they served. The Non-Management Directors and Independent Directors meet regularly in executive sessions. </p>

<a name="_N11411"></a>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:20pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:28pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:22pt; font-weight:bold">


<font color="#007DC3">Board Committees</font>


</p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">The Board has six standing committees: the Audit Committee; the Compensation, Nominating and Governance Committee; the Executive Committee; the Global Compensation Committee; the Strategic Planning and Finance Committee; and the Technology and eCommerce Committee. As described above, the Board has determined that all of the members of the Audit Committee and the Compensation, Nominating and Governance Committee are independent directors within the meaning of the SEC&rsquo;s rules and regulations and the listing standards of the NYSE. The Board as a whole and each Board committee conducts a self-evaluation of its performance on an annual basis. The charters for each committee may be found on Walmart&rsquo;s website at <i>www.stock.walmart.com </i>in the &ldquo;Corporate Governance&rdquo; section.<u></u>

</p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">The chart below summarizes the membership of each committee during fiscal 2013. </p>


<table style="margin-top:3pt; margin-bottom:12pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt;" cellspacing="0" align="center" width="100%" cellpadding="2" frame="void">
<tr>
<td rowspan="1" colspan="1" width="239.8110236220473" style="border-bottom:1.5pt solid #000000; padding-right:0pt;" valign="bottom">

<p style="margin: 0pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;" align="left">
<b>&nbsp;</b>
</p>

</td><td rowspan="1" colspan="1" width="130.5921259842519" style="border-bottom:1.5pt solid #000000; padding-right:0pt;" valign="bottom">

<p style="margin: 0pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;" align="center">
<b>Audit </b>
</p>

<p style="margin: 0pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;" align="center">
<b>Committee</b>

<table style="margin-top:3pt; margin-bottom:12pt; border:1.5pt solid #007DC3; padding-left: 8.5pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt;" cellspacing="0" align="center" width="100%" cellpadding="5" frame="void">
<tr>
<td rowspan="1" colspan="2" width="NaN" valign="centre">
<a name="_N117CD"></a>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:3pt; padding-left:0pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:20pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold ">

<font color="#007DC3">Audit Committee</font>

</p>
<p style="margin-top:1pt; margin-left:0pt; margin-bottom:25pt; border-top:1pt solid #007DC3; line-height:20pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:28pt; font-weight:bold"></p>

</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td rowspan="2" colspan="1" width="805.267716535433" valign="centre">

<p style="margin: 0pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt; color: #000000" align="left">

<b>
<font color="#007DC3">Roles and responsibilities</font>
<b>
<font color="#007DC3"></font>
</b>
</b>

</p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Reviews financial reporting policies, procedures, and internal controls </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Responsible for the appointment, compensation, and oversight of the independent accountants </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Pre-approves audit, audit-related, and non-audit services to be performed by Walmart&rsquo;s independent accountants </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Reviews and approves related-party transactions and other transactions subject to our Transaction Review Policy </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Reviews Walmart&rsquo;s risk management policies and procedures, as well as policies, processes, and procedures regarding compliance with applicable laws and regulations, as well as our Statement of Ethics and Code of Ethics for the CEO and Senior Financial Officers </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Oversees internal investigatory matters, including Walmart&rsquo;s internal investigation into alleged violations of the FCPA and other alleged crimes or misconduct in connection with foreign subsidiaries# </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Oversees the development and implementation of Walmart&rsquo;s enhanced global compliance program </p>

<p style="margin: 0pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt; color: #000000" align="left">

<b>
<font color="#007DC3">Independence and financial literacy</font>
<b>
<font color="#007DC3"></font>
</b>
</b>

</p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">The Board has determined that the members are &ldquo;independent&rdquo; as defined by Section&nbsp;10A(m)(3) of the Exchange Act and the NYSE Listed Company Rules </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">The Board has determined that the members are &ldquo;financially literate&rdquo; as required by Section&nbsp;303A.07 of the NYSE Listed Company Rules</p>

</td><td rowspan="1" colspan="1" width="216.98425196850394" style="background-color:#D9EBF6; padding-right:0pt;vertical-align:baseline;" valign="">

<p style="margin: 0pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt; color: #000000; font-weight: normal" align="left">

<b>
<font color="#007DC3">Committee members </font>
</b>

</p>

<p style="margin: 0pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt; color: #000000; font-weight: normal" align="left">Christopher J. Williams (C, F, I) </p>

<p style="margin: 0pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt; color: #000000; font-weight: normal" align="left">Aida M. Alvarez (I) </p>

<p style="margin: 0pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt; color: #000000; font-weight: normal" align="left">James I. Cash, Jr. (F, I) </p>

<p style="margin-top:16pt; margin-bottom:1pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:12pt; font-family:Arial; font-weight:bold; font-size:12pt;" align="justify">
<font><i>


<table style="margin-top:3pt; margin-bottom:12pt; border:1.5pt solid #007DC3; padding-left: 8.5pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt;" cellspacing="0" align="center" width="100%" cellpadding="5" frame="void">
<tr>
<td rowspan="1" colspan="2" width="NaN" valign="centre">
<a name="_N1182D"></a>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:3pt; padding-left:0pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:20pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold ">

<font color="#007DC3">Compensation, Nominating and Governance Committee</font>

</p>
<p style="margin-top:1pt; margin-left:0pt; margin-bottom:25pt; border-top:1pt solid #007DC3; line-height:20pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:28pt; font-weight:bold"></p>

</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td rowspan="2" colspan="1" width="805.267716535433" valign="centre">

<p style="margin: 0pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt; color: #000000" align="left">

<b>
<font color="#007DC3">Roles and responsibilities</font>
<b>
<font color="#007DC3"></font>
</b>
</b>

</p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">In consultation with the CEO, approves the compensation of the Executive Officers other than the CEO, and reviews the&nbsp;compensation of certain other senior officers </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Reviews and approves the compensation of the CEO and Chairman </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Reviews and makes recommendations to the Board regarding the compensation of the Non-Management Directors </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Sets performance measures and goals and verifies the attainment of performance goals under performance-based incentive compensation plans </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Reviews compensation and benefits issues </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Oversees corporate governance issues </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Identifies, evaluates, and recommends candidates to the Board for nomination for election or appointment to the Board </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Reviews and makes recommendations to the Board regarding director independence </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Reviews and advises management on the company&rsquo;s social, community and sustainability initiatives </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Reviews and advises management on the company&rsquo;s legislative affairs and public policy engagement </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">May delegate compensation matters that do not impact Executive Officers to the GCC and ministerial duties to the company&rsquo;s management </p>

<p style="margin: 0pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt; color: #000000" align="left">

<b>
<font color="#007DC3">Independence</font>
<b>
<font color="#007DC3"></font>
</b>
</b>

</p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">The Board has determined that the members are &ldquo;independent&rdquo; as defined by the NYSE Listed Company Rules and under Section&nbsp;10C of the Exchange Act and Rule 10C-1 of the SEC</p>

</td><td rowspan="1" colspan="1" width="216.98425196850394" style="background-color:#D9EBF6; padding-right:0pt;vertical-align:baseline;" valign="">

<p style="margin: 0pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt; color: #000000; font-weight: normal" align="left">

<b>
<font color="#007DC3">Committee members </font>
</b>

</p>

<p style="margin: 0pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt; color: #000000; font-weight: normal" align="left">Linda S. Wolf (C, I) </p>

<p style="margin: 0pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt; color: #000000; font-weight: normal" align="left">Douglas N. Daft (I) </p>

<p style="margin: 0pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt; color: #000000; font-weight: normal" align="left">Steven S Reinemund (I)</p>

</td>

<p align="justify" style="margin: 0pt; margin-bottom:2.5pt; padding-left: 20pt; line-height:11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-style: normal; font-size: 9pt;"></p>

</p>

</td><td rowspan="1" colspan="1" width="216.98425196850394" style="background-color:#D9EBF6; padding-right:0pt;vertical-align:bottom;" valign="">

<font color="#007DC3">Strategic Planning and Finance Committee</font>

</p>
<p style="margin-top:1pt; margin-left:0pt; margin-bottom:25pt; border-top:1pt solid #007DC3; line-height:20pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:28pt; font-weight:bold"></p>

<b>
<font color="#007DC3">Roles and responsibilities</font>
<b>
<font color="#007DC3"></font>
</b>
</b>

</p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Reviews and analyzes financial matters and acquisitions and divestiture transactions </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Oversees long-range strategic planning </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Reviews and recommends a dividend policy to the Board </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Reviews the preliminary annual financial plan and annual capital plan to be approved by the Board</p>

</td><td rowspan="1" colspan="1" width="216.98425196850394" style="background-color:#D9EBF6; padding-right:0pt;vertical-align:baseline;" valign="">

<p style="margin: 0pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt; color: #000000; font-weight: normal" align="left">

<b>
<font color="#007DC3">Committee members </font>
</b>

</p>

<p style="margin: 0pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt; color: #000000; font-weight: normal" align="left">M. Michele Burns* (C, I) </p>

<p style="margin: 0pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt; color: #000000; font-weight: normal" align="left">James W. Breyer* (I) </p>

<p style="margin: 0pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt; color: #000000; font-weight: normal" align="left">Roger C. Corbett (I) </p>

<p style="margin: 0pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt; color: #000000; font-weight: normal" align="left">Marissa A. Mayer (I) </p>

<p style="margin: 0pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt; color: #000000; font-weight: normal" align="left">H. Lee Scott, Jr.  </p>

<p style="margin: 0pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt; color: #000000; font-weight: normal" align="left">

</p>

</td>
</tr>

</p>

<p align="justify" style="margin: 0pt; margin-bottom:2.5pt; padding-left: 20pt; line-height:11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-style: normal; font-size: 9pt;"></p>

<p align="justify" style="margin: 0pt; margin-bottom:2.5pt; line-height:11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-style: normal; font-size: 9pt;">I = Determined by the Board to be independent under the NYSE Listed Company Rules </p>
<p align="justify" style="margin: 0pt; margin-bottom:2.5pt; padding-left: 20pt; line-height:11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-style: normal; font-size: 9pt;"></p>

</i></font>
</p>


<p style="margin-top:16pt; margin-bottom:1pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:12pt; font-family:Arial; font-weight:bold; font-size:12pt;" align="justify">
<font><i>

<font color="#007DC3">Technology and eCommerce Committee</font>

</p>
<p style="margin-top:1pt; margin-left:0pt; margin-bottom:25pt; border-top:1pt solid #007DC3; line-height:20pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:28pt; font-weight:bold"></p>

</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td rowspan="2" colspan="1" width="805.267716535433" valign="centre">

<p style="margin: 0pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt; color: #000000" align="left">

<b>
<font color="#007DC3">Roles and responsibilities</font>
<b>
<font color="#007DC3"></font>
</b>
</b>

</p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Reviews matters relating to information technology, eCommerce, and innovation and oversees the integration of&nbsp;&nbsp;Walmart&rsquo;s&nbsp;information technology, eCommerce, and innovation efforts with Walmart&rsquo;s overall strategy </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Reviews and provides guidance regarding trends in technology and eCommerce and monitors overall industry trends</p>

</td><td rowspan="1" colspan="1" width="216.98425196850394" style="background-color:#D9EBF6; padding-right:0pt;vertical-align:baseline;" valign="">
