<a name="_N11985"></a>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:30pt;padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:27pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:26pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">

CORPORATE GOVERNANCE

</font>
</p>

<a name="_N11988"></a>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:20pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:28pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:22pt; font-weight:bold">


<font color="#007DC3">Corporate Governance Highlights</font>


</p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">The Board is responsible for overseeing the management of the business and affairs of the company in a manner that serves the long-term best interests of our shareholders. The Board is committed to the highest standards of corporate governance and has implemented a variety of effective governance processes and practices to assist the Board and management in fulfilling their responsibilities to the company and our shareholders, including the following. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">As described below, each of the standing committees of the Board has a written charter, which clearly sets forth the roles and responsibilities of the committee and which, along with the company&rsquo;s Corporate Governance Guidelines, provides the overall framework for our corporate governance practices. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Our directors are elected annually and serve one-year terms. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">We have a majority vote standard in uncontested elections of directors, and any incumbent directors who do not receive a majority vote must offer their resignation. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">A majority of our Board is composed of Independent Directors. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Our Audit Committee and CNGC are composed solely of Independent Directors. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">We have separated the roles of the Chairman and CEO of our company for 25 years. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">We have an independent presiding director who presides over the executive sessions of our Non-Management Directors, which are held at each Board meeting. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">We hold an annual shareholder advisory vote on the compensation of our named executive officers. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">We have robust stock ownership guidelines applicable to our directors, Executive Officers, and certain other officers of the company. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">The Board and Board committees conduct annual self-evaluations to determine whether they are functioning effectively and to identify areas in which their effectiveness can be enhanced. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">The Board and each Board committee have the power to hire independent legal, financial, or other advisors, as they deem necessary, without consulting or obtaining the approval of any officer of the company. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Directors have full and free access to officers and other Associates of the company, as well as to the company&rsquo;s outside advisors. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">The Board recently approved an amendment to the CNGC&rsquo;s charter giving the CNGC oversight of the company&rsquo;s legislative affairs and public policy engagement strategy. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">The Board annually submits the appointment of the company&rsquo;s independent accountants to our shareholders for ratification. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">The company&rsquo;s Insider Trading Policy prohibits directors and Executive Officers from using Shares as collateral for margin loans and from engaging in any hedging or other transactions that would eliminate or limit the risks and rewards of Share ownership. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Directors and Executive Officers are prohibited from pledging Shares for non-margin loans without the pre-approval of Walmart&rsquo;s Corporate Secretary, and any pledged Shares are not considered in determining whether directors or Executive Officers have satisfied our stock ownership guidelines. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">The Board has not adopted a &ldquo;poison pill&rdquo; or similar shareholder rights plan. </p>

<a name="_N119B0"></a>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:20pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:28pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:22pt; font-weight:bold">


<font color="#007DC3">Board and Committee Governing Documents</font>


</p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">The Board has adopted Corporate Governance Guidelines and charters for each of the standing Board committees. Our Corporate Governance Guidelines address, among other topics: </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">director qualifications and nomination requirements; </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Board size, structure, and composition; </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">director stock ownership guidelines; </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">the Board&rsquo;s commitment to diversified membership; </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">director duties and responsibilities; </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">the committees of the Board; </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">expectations regarding attendance at Board and Board committee meetings; </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">the process for establishing the agendas of Board and Board committee meetings; </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">executive sessions of the Non-Management Directors and Independent Directors; </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">management development and succession planning, diversity initiatives, and long-term strategic planning; </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">director compensation; </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">director orientation and continuing education; </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">annual Board and Board committee self-evaluations; and </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">expected periods of service for directors. </p>


<table style="margin-top:3pt; margin-bottom:12pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt;" cellspacing="0" align="center" width="100%" cellpadding="5" frame="void">

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">The CNGC and the Board review the Corporate Governance Guidelines, and the Board and each Board committee review the Board committee charters, at least annually to determine whether any updates or revisions to these documents may be necessary or appropriate. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">In addition to the Corporate Governance Guidelines and the Board committee charters, you may access and review the following additional corporate governance documents on our corporate website at <i>http://stock.walmart.&zwnj;com/corporate-governance/governance-documents</i>: </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Walmart&rsquo;s Code of Ethics for the CEO and Senior Financial Officers supplements Walmart&rsquo;s Statement of Ethics, which is applicable to all directors, Executive Officers, and Associates and is also available at <i>www.walmartethics.com.</i> A&nbsp;description of any substantive amendment or waiver of Walmart&rsquo;s Code of Ethics for the CEO and Senior Financial Officers or Walmart&rsquo;s Statement of Ethics will be disclosed on our corporate website (<i>http://stock.walmart.com/corporate-governance/governance-documents</i>) for a period of 12&nbsp;months after the date of the amendment or waiver. There were no substantive amendments or waivers of Walmart&rsquo;s Code of Ethics for the CEO and Senior Financial Officers or Walmart&rsquo;s Statement of Ethics during fiscal 2013. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">The Corporate Governance Guidelines, Board committee charters, and each of the other documents described above are available in print at no charge to any shareholder who requests a copy by writing to our Investor Relations Department at: Wal-Mart Stores,&nbsp;Inc., Investor Relations Department, 702&nbsp;Southwest 8<sup>th</sup> Street, Bentonville, Arkansas 72716-0100. </p>

<a name="_N11A0C"></a>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:20pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:28pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:22pt; font-weight:bold">


<font color="#007DC3">Board Leadership Structure</font>


</p>


<table style="margin-top:3pt; margin-bottom:12pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt;" cellspacing="0" align="center" width="100%" cellpadding="5" frame="void">
<tr>
<td rowspan="1" colspan="1" width="491.22834645669263" style="border:1.5pt solid #007DC3;" valign="centre">

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">

<b>Chairman:</b>&nbsp;<b>
<i>S.&nbsp;Robson Walton</i>
</b>&nbsp;&ndash; presides over all meetings of the Board and shareholders; provides advice and counsel to the CEO and other officers; focuses on oversight and governance matters </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">

<b>CEO:</b>&nbsp;<b>
<i>Michael T. Duke</i>
</b>&nbsp;&ndash; responsible for general management of the business of the company and effectuating directives of the Board </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">

<b>Presiding Director:</b>&nbsp;<b>
<i>James W. Breyer</i>
</b>&nbsp;&ndash; Independent Director; presides over&nbsp;the&nbsp;executive sessions of the Non-Management Directors and Independent Directors </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Additional information about Mr.&nbsp;Walton, Mr.&nbsp;Duke, and Mr.&nbsp;Breyer may be found on pages&nbsp;19, 23, and 24.</p>

</td>
</tr>
</table>


<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">We have separated the roles of the Chairman and the CEO of our company since 1988. We separate these roles in recognition of the differences between the two roles and the value to our company of having the distinct and different perspectives and experiences of a separate Chairman and CEO. Our CEO is responsible for the day-to-day management and supervision of the business and affairs of our company (such as reviewing performance and allocating resources as the company&rsquo;s chief operating decision maker) and for ensuring that the directives of the Board are carried into effect. Our Chairman, on the other hand, is charged with presiding over all meetings of the Board and our shareholders, and providing advice and counsel to the CEO and our company&rsquo;s other officers regarding our business and operations. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">By separating the roles of CEO and Chairman, our CEO is able to focus his time and energy on managing Walmart&rsquo;s complex daily operations, while our Chairman can devote his time and attention to addressing matters relating to the responsibilities of our Board. Our CEO and Chairman have an excellent working relationship, and, with more than 40 years of experience with Walmart, our Chairman is well positioned to provide our CEO with guidance, advice, and counsel regarding our company&rsquo;s business, operations, and strategy. Moreover, we believe that having a separate Chairman focused on oversight and governance matters allows the Board to more effectively perform its risk oversight role as described below. In connection with the Board&rsquo;s annual self-evaluation process, as required by our Corporate Governance Guidelines, the Board evaluates its organization and processes to ensure that the Board is functioning effectively. For the foregoing reasons, we believe that our separate CEO/Chairman structure is the most appropriate and effective leadership structure for our company and our shareholders. </p>

<a name="_N11A37"></a>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:20pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:28pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:22pt; font-weight:bold">


<font color="#007DC3">Presiding Director</font>


</p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Pursuant to the company&rsquo;s Corporate Governance Guidelines, the Board, upon recommendation of the CNGC, annually appoints a presiding director who presides over executive sessions of the Non-Management Directors and Independent Directors. James W. Breyer currently serves as the presiding director.  Upon the completion of Mr. Breyer&rsquo;s term at the 2013 Annual Shareholders&rsquo; Meeting, the Board will appoint another Independent Director to serve as presiding director. </p>

<a name="_N11A3D"></a>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:20pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:28pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:22pt; font-weight:bold">


<font color="#007DC3">The Board&rsquo;s Role in Risk Oversight</font>


</p>

<table style="margin-top:3pt; margin-bottom:12pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt;" cellspacing="0" align="center" width="100%" cellpadding="5" frame="void">
<tr>
<td rowspan="1" colspan="1" width="491.22834645669263" style="border:1.5pt solid #007DC3;" valign="centre">

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">The Board oversees the company&rsquo;s risk management. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">The Board committees, which meet regularly and report to the full Board, play active roles in fulfilling the risk oversight function. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">The company&rsquo;s management is responsible for day-to-day management of risk and are guided by robust internal processes and strong internal controls.</p>

</td>
</tr>
</table>


<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">In order to ensure the long-term success and financial strength of our company, the Board and the Board committees play an active role in overseeing the management of risks that could potentially impact the company&rsquo;s operations. Such risks could include operational, legal, regulatory, financial, reputational, and other risks. The Board does not view risk in isolation, but instead considers risk in connection with virtually every business decision and as part of the company&rsquo;s approach to its business strategy. The company has robust internal processes and a strong internal control environment that facilitate the identification and management of risk by the company&rsquo;s leadership, the Board, and the Board committees. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">The Board carries out its risk oversight function both as a whole and through delegation to the Board committees, which report regularly to the Board. The Audit Committee is responsible for reviewing and discussing with management </p>

<p style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 3pt; padding-left: 17.2pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;" align="justify"></p>
<p style="margin:0pt; margin-top:14pt; margin-bottom: 14pt; line-height:10pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt;" align="right">
<img src="footer_walmart.jpg" style="margin-bottom:-5pt;">&nbsp;&nbsp;<i>2013 Proxy Statement</i>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;33</p>
<hr>
<p style="page-break-before:always; margin:0pt; margin-bottom: 28pt; line-height:10pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt;">
<a href="#_TOC"><font color="#0000FF">Back to Contents</font></a>
</p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">
the company&rsquo;s risk assessment and risk management processes and policies, including the company&rsquo;s enterprise-wide risk management program, as well as the company&rsquo;s financial and other risk exposures and the steps management has taken to monitor and control such exposures. The Audit Committee is also responsible for discussing with management and advising the Board with respect to the company&rsquo;s policies, processes, and procedures regarding compliance with applicable laws and regulations, the company&rsquo;s Statement of Ethics, and the company&rsquo;s Code of Ethics for the CEO and Senior Financial Officers. The Audit Committee meets regularly with the company&rsquo;s Global Chief Compliance Officer, Global Chief Ethics Officer, and other appropriate members of management regarding the implementation and effectiveness of the company&rsquo;s compliance and ethics programs. In addition, the Audit Committee oversees internal investigatory matters, including Walmart&rsquo;s internal investigation into alleged violations of the FCPA and other alleged crimes or misconduct in connection with foreign subsidiaries, and oversees the development and implementation of Walmart&rsquo;s enhanced global compliance program.   </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">The other Board committees also play a significant role in the Board&rsquo;s oversight of risk. For example, the CNGC is charged with developing and recommending to the Board the corporate governance principles applicable to the company; implementing incentive compensation programs with features that mitigate risk without diminishing the incentive nature of the compensation; reviewing and assessing the company&rsquo;s compliance with the corporate governance requirements established by the NYSE, the requirements established under SOX and the Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act, and other applicable corporate governance laws and regulations; reviewing and advising the Board and management regarding the company&rsquo;s reputation with external constituencies, the company&rsquo;s social, community, sustainability, and charitable giving initiatives and strategies; and reviewing and advising management regarding the company&rsquo;s legislative affairs and public policy engagement strategy. Furthermore, the SPFC regularly reviews with management the company&rsquo;s financial status and advises management and the Board regarding financial matters, including the company&rsquo;s global financial policies and practices, the company&rsquo;s capital structure and capital expenditures, annual financial plans, and matters pertaining to potential acquisitions and divestitures. The CNGC&rsquo;s and the SPFC&rsquo;s review of these matters necessarily includes an analysis of any risks associated with such matters. Additional information regarding the roles and responsibilities of our Board committees can be found under &ldquo;Board Committees&rdquo; beginning on page 29. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">When a Board committee receives an update on a risk-related matter, the chair of the relevant Board committee reports on the discussion to the full Board during the Board committee reports portion of the next Board meeting. The open communication between the company&rsquo;s management and the Board and the Board committees, and between the Board and the chairs and the other members of the Board committees, enables the Board, Board committees, and management to coordinate the risk oversight role in a manner that serves the long-term interests of the company and our shareholders. </p>

<a name="_N11A5E"></a>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:20pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:28pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:22pt; font-weight:bold">


<font color="#007DC3">Board Attendance at Annual Shareholders&rsquo; Meetings</font>


</p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">The Board has adopted a policy stating that all directors are expected to attend the company&rsquo;s annual shareholders&rsquo; meetings. While the Board understands that there may be situations that prevent a director from attending an annual shareholders&rsquo; meeting, the Board encourages all directors to make attendance at all annual shareholders&rsquo; meetings a priority. With the exception of Mr.&nbsp;Reinemund, all of our directors who were members of the Board at the time of the 2012 Annual Shareholders&rsquo; Meeting attended the meeting. </p>

<a name="_N11A64"></a>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:20pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:28pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:22pt; font-weight:bold">


<font color="#007DC3">Communications with the Board</font>


</p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">The Board welcomes communications from shareholders and other interested parties and believes that such communications are an important part of our corporate governance practices. Therefore, we provide shareholders and other interested parties with a number of methods for communicating with the Board or individual directors. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Shareholders and other interested parties may write to the Board or individual members of the Board at: </p>


<table style="margin-top:3pt; margin-bottom:12pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt;" cellspacing="0" align="center" width="100%" cellpadding="2" frame="void">
<tr>
<td rowspan="1" colspan="1" width="73.47401574803149" style="padding-right:0pt;vertical-align:top;" valign="">
<p style="margin: 0pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt; color: #000000" align="center"><img src="graphic_mail.jpg"></p></td>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Our company receives a large volume of correspondence regarding a wide range of subjects each day. As a result, our individual directors are often not able to respond to all communications directly. Therefore, our Board has established a process for managing communications to the Board and individual directors. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Communications directed to the Board or individual directors are reviewed to determine whether, based on the facts and circumstances of the communication, a response on behalf of the Board or an individual director is appropriate. If a response on behalf of the Board or an individual director is appropriate, Walmart will assist the Board or individual director in gathering all relevant information and preparing a proposed response for the Board&rsquo;s or the individual director&rsquo;s review and approval. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Communications related to day-to-day management functions or operations are typically directed to an appropriate member of management for a response. Further, Walmart will typically not distribute to the Board or an individual director communications of a threatening or personal nature, voluminous or mass mailings on the same subject matter, business solicitations or advertisements, surveys, or other communications otherwise inappropriate for the Board&rsquo;s or an individual director&rsquo;s consideration. Walmart maintains records of communications directed to the Board and individual directors, and these records are available to our directors at any time upon request. </p>

<p style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 3pt; padding-left: 17.2pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;" align="justify"></p>
<p style="margin:0pt; margin-top:14pt; margin-bottom: 14pt; line-height:10pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt;" align="right">

<a name="_N11AAA"></a>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:20pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:28pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:22pt; font-weight:bold">


<font color="#007DC3">Shareholder Outreach and Engagement</font>


</p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">The company&rsquo;s relationship with its shareholders is a critical part of our corporate governance profile, and we recognize the value of taking their views into account. We value comments from shareholders, customers, and others about our business, and we appreciate that we receive input from so many stakeholders on a daily basis. Specifically related to the investment community, we receive regular analysts&rsquo; reports about our business and interact from time to time with analysts, banks, and rating agencies. This feedback helps us improve. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Our company&rsquo;s investor relations (&ldquo;IR&rdquo;) department is the key point of contact for shareholder interaction with the company. Shareholders may access information about our company through our website at <i>http://stock.walmart.com.</i> This website features a wide variety of information relevant to shareholders, including our Annual Reports to Shareholders, Global Responsibility Reports, SEC reports, proxy statements, and stock information, among other items. Shareholders can also contact IR through our investor hotline at (479) 273-6463, through email at <i>wmirqa@walmart.com</i>, or through providing feedback via our IR smartphone app. The Walmart IR smartphone app is free and available for iPad, iPhone, and Android devices. IR responds to inquiries from all shareholders&nbsp;&ndash; ranging from individuals to institutional shareholders&nbsp;&ndash; and conveys the company&rsquo;s position on a wide range of issues that matter to our shareholders. When appropriate, the IR team partners with subject matter experts from other company departments, such as legal, sustainability, operations, and other areas to provide additional context and insight regarding the company&rsquo;s response to a shareholder inquiry. We have had success engaging with parties to understand shareholder concerns and reaching resolutions on issues that are in the best interest of our shareholders. Beyond our standard means of communication, in 2012, we also conducted activities and events such as store tours, investor road shows, analyst meetings, investor conferences, and the 2012 Annual Shareholders&rsquo; Meeting. </p>

<a name="_N11AB8"></a>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:20pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:28pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:22pt; font-weight:bold">


<font color="#007DC3">Submission of Shareholder Proposals</font>


</p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">If you wish to submit a proposal for possible inclusion in our 2014 proxy statement, send the proposal, by registered, certified, or express mail to: </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="center">Gordon&nbsp;Y. Allison, Vice President and General Counsel, Corporate Division </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="center">702 Southwest 8th Street </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:12pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="center">Bentonville, Arkansas 72716-0215 </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Shareholder proposals intended for inclusion in our proxy statement for the 2014 Annual Shareholders&rsquo; Meeting in accordance with the SEC&rsquo;s Rule 14a-8 under the Exchange Act must be received by our company in the manner described above no later than the close of business on December&nbsp;23,&nbsp;2013. Any shareholder proposal received by the company after that date will not be included in the company&rsquo;s 2014 proxy statement. Further, all proposals submitted for inclusion in the company&rsquo;s 2014 proxy statement must comply with all of the requirements of Rule 14a-8. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Shareholders who wish to bring business before Walmart&rsquo;s 2014 Annual Shareholders&rsquo; Meeting other than through a shareholder proposal pursuant to the SEC&rsquo;s rules must notify the Corporate Secretary of our company in writing and provide the information required by the provision of the Bylaws dealing with shareholder proposals. The notice must be delivered to or mailed and received at Walmart&rsquo;s principal executive offices not less than 75 nor more than 100 days prior to the date of the 2014 Annual Shareholders&rsquo; Meeting, unless fewer than 85 days&rsquo; notice or public disclosure of that date is given or made, in which case the shareholder&rsquo;s notice must be received by the close of business on the tenth day after the notice or public disclosure of the date of the 2014 Annual Shareholders&rsquo; Meeting is made or given. The requirements for such notice are set forth in the Bylaws, a copy of which can be found on our corporate website at <i>http://stock.walmart.com/corporate-governance/governance-documents</i>. In&nbsp;addition, the Bylaws were filed with the SEC as Exhibit 3(ii) to our company&rsquo;s Quarterly Report on Form&nbsp;10-Q for the quarterly period ended April&nbsp;30,&nbsp;2011. </p>

<a name="_N11ACB"></a>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:20pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:28pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:22pt; font-weight:bold">

</p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">The CNGC has reviewed and discussed with our company&rsquo;s management the CD&amp;A included in this proxy statement and, based on such review and discussion, the CNGC recommended to the Board that the CD&amp;A be included in this proxy statement. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">The CNGC submits this report: </p>

<a name="_N11ADE"></a>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:20pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:28pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:22pt; font-weight:bold">


<font color="#007DC3">Compensation Committee Interlocks and Insider Participation</font>


</p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">None of the directors who served on the CNGC at any time during fiscal 2013 were officers or Associates of Walmart or were former officers or Associates of Walmart. Further, none of the members who served on the CNGC at any time during fiscal 2013 had any relationship with our company requiring disclosure under the section of this proxy statement entitled &ldquo;Related Person Transactions.&rdquo; Finally, no Executive Officer serves, or in the past fiscal year has served, as a member of the compensation committee (or other board committee performing equivalent functions) of any entity that has one or more of its executive officers serving on the CNGC. </p>

<a name="_N11AE4"></a>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:20pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:28pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:22pt; font-weight:bold">


<font color="#007DC3">Audit Committee Report</font>


</p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">

<i>Information regarding the members of the Audit Committee and the Audit Committee&rsquo;s roles and responsibilities is set forth under &ldquo;&ldquo;Compensation of the Directors&rdquo; on page&nbsp;</i>26<i> and &ldquo;Board Committees&rdquo; beginning on page </i>29<i>.</i>

</p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Walmart&rsquo;s management is responsible for Walmart&rsquo;s internal control over financial reporting and the preparation of Walmart&rsquo;s consolidated financial statements. Walmart&rsquo;s independent accountants are responsible for auditing Walmart&rsquo;s annual consolidated financial statements in accordance with the standards of the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board, and for auditing the effectiveness of Walmart&rsquo;s internal control over financial reporting. The independent accountants are also responsible for issuing a report on those financial statements and a report on the effectiveness of Walmart&rsquo;s internal control over financial reporting. The Audit Committee monitors and oversees these processes. The Audit Committee is responsible for selecting, engaging, and overseeing Walmart&rsquo;s independent accountants. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">As part of the oversight process, the Audit Committee regularly meets with management of our company, our company&rsquo;s independent accountants, and our company&rsquo;s internal auditors. The Audit Committee often meets with each of these groups separately in closed sessions. Throughout the year, the Audit Committee had full access to management, the independent accountants and internal auditors. To fulfill its responsibilities, the Audit Committee did, among other things, the following: </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">reviewed and discussed with Walmart&rsquo;s management and the independent accountants Walmart&rsquo;s audited consolidated financial statements for fiscal 2013; </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">reviewed management&rsquo;s representations that those consolidated financial statements were prepared in accordance with GAAP and fairly present the consolidated results of operations and consolidated financial position of our company for the fiscal years and as of the dates covered by those consolidated financial statements; </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">discussed with the independent accountants the matters required by Statement on Auditing Standards No. 61, as modified or supplemented, and SEC rules, including matters related to the conduct of the audit of Walmart&rsquo;s consolidated financial statements; </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">received written disclosures and the letter from E&amp;Y required by applicable independence standards, rules, and regulations relating to E&amp;Y&rsquo;s independence from Walmart and discussed with E&amp;Y its independence from Walmart; </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">based on the review and discussions with management and the independent accountants, the independent accountants&rsquo; disclosures and letter to the Audit Committee, the representations of management and the reports of the independent accountants, recommended to the Board that Walmart&rsquo;s audited consolidated financial statements for fiscal 2013 be included in Walmart&rsquo;s Annual Report on Form&nbsp;10-K for fiscal 2013 filed with the SEC; </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">reviewed all audit and non-audit services performed for Walmart by E&amp;Y and considered whether E&amp;Y&rsquo;s provision of non-audit services was compatible with maintaining its independence from Walmart; </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">selected and appointed E&amp;Y as Walmart&rsquo;s independent accountants to audit and report on the consolidated financial statements of Walmart to be filed with the SEC prior to Walmart&rsquo;s annual shareholders&rsquo; meeting to be held in calendar year 2014; </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">monitored the progress and results of the testing of internal control over financial reporting pursuant to Section&nbsp;404 of SOX, reviewed a report from management and the internal auditors of our company regarding the design, operation, and effectiveness of internal control over financial reporting, and reviewed an attestation report from E&amp;Y regarding the effectiveness of internal control over financial reporting; and </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">received reports from management and third-party advisors regarding our company&rsquo;s policies, processes, and procedures regarding compliance with applicable laws and regulations and Walmart&rsquo;s Statement of Ethics, all in accordance with the Audit Committee&rsquo;s charter. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">The Audit Committee submits this report: </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 2pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Aida M. Alvarez </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 2pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">James I. Cash, Jr. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 2pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Timothy P. Flynn </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 2pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Arne M. Sorenson </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Christopher J. Williams, <i>Chair </i>

</p>

<a name="_N11B15"></a>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:20pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:28pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:22pt; font-weight:bold">


<font color="#007DC3">Audit Committee Financial Experts</font>


</p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">The Board has determined that James I. Cash, Jr., Timothy P. Flynn, Arne M. Sorenson, and Christopher J. Williams are &ldquo;audit committee financial experts&rdquo; as that term is defined in Item&nbsp;407(d)(5)(ii) of Regulation S-K of the SEC, and that all members of the Audit Committee are &ldquo;independent&rdquo; under Section&nbsp;10A(m)(3) of the Exchange Act, the SEC&rsquo;s Rule 10A-3, and the requirements set forth in the NYSE Listed Company Rules. </p>

<p style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 3pt; padding-left: 17.2pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;" align="justify"></p>

<a name="_N11B1E"></a>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:20pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:28pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:22pt; font-weight:bold">


<font color="#007DC3">Audit Committee Pre-Approval Policy</font>


</p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">To ensure the independence of our independent accountants and to comply with applicable securities laws, the NYSE Listed Company Rules, and the Audit Committee charter, the Audit Committee is responsible for reviewing, deliberating, and, if appropriate, pre-approving all audit, audit-related, and non-audit services to be performed by the independent accountants. For that purpose, the Audit Committee has established a policy and related procedures regarding the pre-approval of all audit, audit-related, and non-audit services to be performed by our company&rsquo;s independent accountants (the &ldquo;Pre-Approval Policy&rdquo;). </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">The Pre-Approval Policy provides that our company&rsquo;s independent accountants may not perform any audit, audit-related, or non-audit service for Walmart, subject to those exceptions that may be permitted by applicable law, unless:&nbsp;(i)&nbsp;the service has been pre-approved by the Audit Committee; or&nbsp;(ii)&nbsp;Walmart engaged the independent accountants to perform the service pursuant to the pre-approval provisions of the Pre-Approval Policy. In addition, the Pre-Approval Policy prohibits the Audit Committee from pre-approving certain non-audit services that are prohibited from being performed by our company&rsquo;s independent accountants by applicable securities laws. The Pre-Approval Policy also provides that Walmart&rsquo;s corporate controller will periodically update the Audit Committee as to services provided by the independent accountants. With respect to each such service, the independent accountants provide detailed back-up documentation to the Audit Committee and to the corporate controller. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Pursuant to the Pre-Approval Policy, the Audit Committee has pre-approved certain categories of services to be performed by the independent accountants and a maximum amount of fees for each category. The Audit Committee annually reassesses these service categories and the associated fees. Individual projects within the approved service categories have been pre-approved only to the extent that the fees for each individual project do not exceed a specified dollar limit, which amount is reassessed annually. Projects within a pre-approved service category with fees in excess of the specified fee limit for individual projects may not proceed without the specific prior approval of the Audit Committee (or a member to whom pre-approval authority has been delegated). In addition, no project within a pre-approved service category will be considered to have been pre-approved by the Audit Committee if the project would cause the maximum amount of fees for the service category to be exceeded, and the project may only proceed with the prior approval of the Audit Committee (or a member to whom pre-approval authority has been delegated) to increase the aggregate amount of fees for the service category. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">At least annually, the Audit Committee designates a member of the Audit Committee to whom it delegates its pre-approval responsibilities. That member has the authority to approve interim requests as set forth above within the defined, pre-approved service categories, as well as interim requests to engage Walmart&rsquo;s independent accountants for services outside the Audit Committee&rsquo;s pre-approved service categories. The member has the authority to pre-approve any audit, audit-related, or non-audit service that falls outside the pre-approved service categories, provided that the member determines that the service would not compromise the independent accountants&rsquo; independence and the member informs the Audit Committee of his or her decision at the Audit Committee&rsquo;s next regular meeting. </p>

<a name="_N11B2A"></a>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:20pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:28pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:22pt; font-weight:bold">


<font color="#007DC3">Transaction Review Policy</font>


</p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">The Board has adopted a written policy (the &ldquo;Transaction Review Policy&rdquo;) applicable to: all Walmart officers who serve as Executive Vice Presidents or above; all directors and director nominees; all shareholders beneficially owning more than five&nbsp;percent of Walmart&rsquo;s outstanding Shares; and the immediate family members of each of the preceding persons (collectively, the &ldquo;Covered Persons&rdquo;). Any entity in which a Covered Person has a direct or indirect material financial interest or of which a Covered Person is an officer or holds a significant management position (each a &ldquo;Covered Entity&rdquo;) is also covered by the policy. The Transaction Review Policy applies to any transaction or series of similar or related transactions in which a Covered Person or Covered Entity has a direct or indirect material financial interest and in which Walmart is a participant (each a &ldquo;Covered Transaction&rdquo;). </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Under the Transaction Review Policy, each Covered Person is responsible for reporting to Walmart&rsquo;s Chief Audit Executive any Covered Transactions of which he or she has knowledge. Walmart&rsquo;s Chief Audit Executive, with the assistance of other appropriate Walmart personnel, reviews each Covered Transaction and submits the results of such review to the Audit Committee. The Audit Committee reviews each Covered Transaction and either approves or disapproves the transaction. To approve a Covered Transaction, the Audit Committee must find that: </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">the substantive terms and negotiation of the Covered Transaction are fair to Walmart and its shareholders and the substantive terms are no less favorable to Walmart and its shareholders than those in similar transactions negotiated at an arm&rsquo;s-length basis; and </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">if the Covered Person is a director or officer of Walmart, he or she has otherwise complied with the terms of Walmart&rsquo;s Statement of Ethics as it applies to the Covered Transaction. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">The Audit Committee may also ratify a Covered Transaction of which prior approval and review was not sought if the Audit Committee determines that the Covered Transaction meets the criteria above and the failure to obtain pre-approval was unintentional or inadvertent. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">The following categories of transactions are exempt from review and approval under the Transaction Review Policy: </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">transactions that involve a monetary value of less than $120,000; </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">transactions that result from a competitive bid process; </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">ordinary banking transactions; and </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">any series of substantially similar transactions after the Audit Committee has reviewed and approved a single transaction of that type as meeting the requirements of the policy. </p>

<p style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 3pt; padding-left: 17.2pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;" align="justify"></p>
<p style="margin:0pt; margin-top:14pt; margin-bottom: 14pt; line-height:10pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt;" align="right">
<img src="footer_walmart.jpg" style="margin-bottom:-5pt;">&nbsp;&nbsp;<i>2013 Proxy Statement</i>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;37</p>

<a href="#_TOC"><font color="#0000FF">Back to Contents</font></a>
</p>

<a name="_N11B45"></a>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:20pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:28pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:22pt; font-weight:bold">


<font color="#007DC3">Related Person Transactions</font>


</p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">This section discusses certain direct and indirect relationships and transactions involving Walmart and certain of its directors, Executive Officers, the beneficial owners of more than five&nbsp;percent of the Shares outstanding, and certain immediate family members of the foregoing. Walmart believes that the terms of the transactions described below are comparable to terms that would have been reached by unrelated parties in arm&rsquo;s-length transactions. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Dr. G. David Gearhart, the Chancellor of the University of Arkansas at Fayetteville (the &ldquo;University&rdquo;), is the brother of Jeffrey J. Gearhart, an Executive Officer. During fiscal 2013, Walmart paid the University approximately $2.3&nbsp;million, including approximately $962,000 for the use of facilities of the University in connection with Walmart&rsquo;s 2012 Annual Shareholders&rsquo; Meeting, the meetings of Associates held during the week of the 2012 Annual Shareholders&rsquo; Meeting, and other meetings and events during fiscal 2013; approximately $523,800 for academic studies and educational services; and approximately $553,000 in contributions and sponsorships. Walmart expects that in fiscal 2014 it will continue to use University facilities for similar events, pay the University for studies and services, and make similar contributions to the University. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Lori Haynie, the sister of C. Douglas McMillon, an Executive Officer, is an executive officer of Mahco, Incorporated (&ldquo;Mahco&rdquo;). During fiscal 2013, Walmart paid Mahco and its subsidiaries approximately $13.0&nbsp;million in connection with Walmart&rsquo;s purchases of sporting goods and related products. Walmart expects to purchase similar types of products from Mahco during fiscal 2014. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Marissa A. Mayer, a director of Walmart, is the president and chief executive officer and a director of Yahoo! Inc. (&ldquo;Yahoo!&rdquo;). During fiscal 2013, Walmart paid Yahoo! and its subsidiaries approximately $12.4&nbsp;million in connection with Walmart&rsquo;s purchases of advertising space on Yahoo! websites. Walmart expects to purchase similar amounts of advertising space from Yahoo! during fiscal 2014. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Eric S. Scott, the son of H. Lee Scott, Jr., a director of Walmart, is the chairman, a director, and an indirect equity owner of Cheyenne Industries,&nbsp;Inc. (&ldquo;Cheyenne&rdquo;). Walmart paid Cheyenne and its subsidiaries approximately $29.4&nbsp;million during fiscal 2013 in connection with Walmart&rsquo;s purchases of home furnishing and related products from Cheyenne and its subsidiaries. Cheyenne and its subsidiaries made promotional payments of approximately $145,000 to Walmart in fiscal 2013. Walmart expects to continue to purchase similar products from Cheyenne and its subsidiaries during fiscal 2014. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Arne M. Sorenson, a director of Walmart, is the president and chief executive officer and a director of Marriott International,&nbsp;Inc. (&ldquo;Marriott&rdquo;). During fiscal 2013, Walmart paid or reimbursed payments made to Marriott and its subsidiaries in the amount of approximately $10.2&nbsp;million for hotel, lodging, and business travel-related services, and Walmart received payments of approximately $2.0&nbsp;million from Marriott for purchases of merchandise from Walmart. Walmart anticipates that it will continue to purchase hotel, lodging, and other business travel-related services from Marriott, and Marriott will continue to purchase merchandise from Walmart during fiscal 2014. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">During fiscal 2013, a banking corporation that is collectively owned by Jim C. Walton, S. Robson Walton, and a trust of which Jim C. Walton is the trustee, and certain of that banking corporation&rsquo;s bank subsidiaries, made payments to Walmart in the approximate aggregate amount of $996,000 for supercenter and Neighborhood Market banking facility rent pursuant to negotiated arrangements. The banking corporation and its affiliates made other payments to Walmart pursuant to similar arrangements that were awarded by Walmart on a competitive-bid basis. The leases of banking facility space and leases of ATM sites in various stores remain in effect, and it is anticipated that in fiscal 2014 such banking corporation and its affiliates will pay Walmart approximately $1.0&nbsp;million pursuant to those leases not awarded on a competitive-bid basis, and will pay Walmart approximately $130,000 relating to ATM usage charges. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Stephen P. Weber, a senior manager in Walmart&rsquo;s Information Systems Division, is the son-in-law of Michael T. Duke, an Executive Officer. For fiscal 2013, Walmart paid Mr.&nbsp;Weber a salary of approximately $127,235, a payment pursuant to the MIP of approximately $24,000, and other benefits totaling approximately $16,100 (including Walmart&rsquo;s matching contributions to Mr.&nbsp;Weber&rsquo;s 401(k) Plan account and health insurance premiums). Mr.&nbsp;Weber also received a grant of 504 restricted stock rights in fiscal 2013. Mr.&nbsp;Weber continues to be an Associate, and in fiscal 2014, he may receive compensation and other benefits for his services to Walmart in amounts similar to those received during fiscal 2013. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Nichole R. Bray, a senior manager at Sam&rsquo;s Club, is the sister-in-law of C. Douglas McMillon, an Executive Officer.  For fiscal 2013, Walmart paid Ms. Bray a salary of approximately $122,200, a payment pursuant to the MIP of approximately $22,700, and other benefits totaling approximately $13,900 (including Walmart&rsquo;s matching contributions to Ms. Bray&rsquo;s 401(k) Plan account and health insurance premiums).  Ms. Bray also received a grant of 504 restricted stock rights in fiscal 2013.  Ms. Bray continues to be an Associate, and in fiscal 2014, she may receive compensation and other benefits in amounts similar to those received during fiscal 2013. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Greg T. Bray, a senior director in Walmart&rsquo;s Finance department, is the brother-in-law of C. Douglas McMillon, an Executive Officer.  For fiscal 2013, Walmart paid Mr. Bray a salary of approximately $160,250, a payment pursuant to the MIP of approximately $35,900, and other benefits totaling approximately $15,100 (including Walmart&rsquo;s matching contributions to Mr. Bray&rsquo;s 401(k) Plan account and health insurance premiums).  Mr. Bray also received a grant of 588 restricted stock rights in fiscal 2013.  Mr. Bray continues to be an Associate, and in fiscal 2014, he may receive compensation and other benefits in amounts similar to those received during fiscal 2013. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Timothy K. Togami, a senior director in Walmart&rsquo;s Human Resources Department, is the brother-in-law of Rollin L. Ford, an Executive Officer. For fiscal 2013, Walmart paid Mr.&nbsp;Togami a salary of approximately $178,600, a payment pursuant to the MIP of approximately $38,375, and other benefits totaling approximately $22,500 (including Walmart&rsquo;s matching contributions to Mr.&nbsp;Togami&rsquo;s 401(k) Plan account and health insurance premiums). Mr.&nbsp;Togami also received a grant of 588 restricted stock rights in fiscal 2013. Mr.&nbsp;Togami continues to be an Associate, and in fiscal 2014, he may receive compensation and other benefits for his services to Walmart in amounts similar to those received during fiscal 2013. </p>

<a name="_N11B62"></a>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:30pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:28pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:26pt; font-weight:bold">
<font color="#007DC3">Proposal No.&nbsp;2</font>&nbsp;&nbsp;Ratification of Independent Accountants </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">The Audit Committee has appointed E&amp;Y as the company&rsquo;s independent accountants to audit the consolidated financial statements of the company for fiscal 2014. E&amp;Y and its predecessor, Arthur Young&nbsp;&amp; Company, have been Walmart&rsquo;s independent accountants since prior to the company&rsquo;s initial offering of securities to the public in 1970. E&amp;Y served as the company&rsquo;s independent accountants for fiscal 2013 and reported on the company&rsquo;s consolidated financial statements for that year, as well as the effectiveness of the company&rsquo;s internal control over financial reporting. Representatives of E&amp;Y will attend the 2013 Annual Shareholders&rsquo; Meeting. They will have the opportunity to make a statement if they desire to do so and to respond to appropriate questions. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Although shareholder ratification is not required, the appointment of E&amp;Y as the company&rsquo;s independent accountants for fiscal 2014 is being submitted for ratification at the 2013 Annual Shareholders&rsquo; Meeting because the Board believes doing so is a good corporate governance practice. Furthermore, the Audit Committee will take shareholders&rsquo; opinions regarding E&amp;Y&rsquo;s appointment into consideration in future deliberations. If E&amp;Y&rsquo;s selection is not ratified at the 2013 Annual Shareholders&rsquo; Meeting, the Audit Committee will consider the engagement of other independent accountants. The Audit Committee may terminate E&amp;Y&rsquo;s engagement as the company&rsquo;s independent accountants without the approval of the company&rsquo;s shareholders whenever the Audit Committee deems termination appropriate. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">E&amp;Y&rsquo;s fees for fiscal 2013 and fiscal 2012 were as follows: </p>
