<a name="_N15E4C"></a>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:30pt;padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:27pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:26pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">

SHAREHOLDER PROPOSALS

</font>
</p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Our company has received notice of the intention of shareholders to present four separate proposals for voting at the 2013 Annual Shareholders&rsquo; Meeting. The text of the shareholder proposals and supporting statements appear exactly as received by our company. All statements contained in a shareholder proposal and supporting statement are the sole responsibility of the proponent of that shareholder proposal. Our company will provide the names, addresses, and shareholdings (to our company&rsquo;s knowledge) of the proponents of any shareholder proposal upon oral or written request made to Wal-Mart Stores,&nbsp;Inc., c/o Gordon Y. Allison, Vice President and General Counsel, Corporate Division, 702 Southwest 8<sup>th</sup> Street, Bentonville, Arkansas 72716-0215, (479) 273-4000. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">The Board recommends a vote against each of the following shareholder proposals based on broader policy reasons as set forth in Walmart&rsquo;s statements in opposition following each shareholder proposal. In our statements in opposition, we have not attempted to refute all of the assertions made about Walmart in the shareholder proposals. </p>

<p style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 3pt; padding-left: 17.2pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;" align="justify"></p>
<p style="margin:0pt; margin-top:14pt; margin-bottom: 14pt; line-height:10pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt;" align="right">
<img src="footer_walmart.jpg" style="margin-bottom:-5pt;">&nbsp;&nbsp;<i>2013 Proxy Statement</i>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;69</p>
<hr>
<p style="page-break-before:always; margin:0pt; margin-bottom: 28pt; line-height:10pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt;">
<a href="#_TOC"><font color="#0000FF">Back to Contents</font></a>
</p>

<a name="_N15E59"></a>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:30pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:28pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:26pt; font-weight:bold">
<font color="#007DC3">Proposal No.&nbsp;5</font>&nbsp;&nbsp;Special Shareowner Meeting Right </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">

<b>RESOLVED:</b> Shareowners ask our board to take the steps necessary unilaterally (to the fullest extent permitted by law) to amend our bylaws and each appropriate governing document to give holders of 10% of our outstanding common stock (or the lowest&nbsp;percentage permitted by law above 10%) the power to call a special shareowner meeting. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">This includes that such bylaw and/or charter text will not have any exclusionary or prohibitive language in regard to calling a special meeting that apply only to shareowners but not to management and/or the board (to the fullest extent permitted by law). This proposal does not impact our board&rsquo;s current power to call a special meeting. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Special meetings allow shareowners to vote on important matters, such as electing new directors that can arise between annual meetings. Shareowner input on the timing of shareowner meetings is especially important when events unfold quickly and issues may become moot by the next annual meeting. This proposal topic won more than 60% support at CVS, Sprint and Safeway. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">This proposal should also be evaluated in the context of our Company&rsquo;s overall corporate governance as reported in 2012: </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">GMI/The Corporate Library, an independent investment research firm, had rated our company &ldquo;D&rdquo; continuously since the first term of the Bush administration with &ldquo;High Governance Risk.&rdquo; Also &ldquo;Concern&rdquo; for our director&rsquo;s qualifications and &ldquo;High Concern&rdquo; in Executive Pay -$20&nbsp;million for Michael Duke. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Mr.&nbsp;Duke&rsquo;s annual incentive pay relied on only one performance goal, operating income. A mix of performance goals is better, not just to prevent our executives from the temptation to game results, but to ensure that they do not take actions to achieve one goal that might ultimately damage another. Despite missing operating income targets Mr.&nbsp;Duke received $3&nbsp;million in annual incentive pay. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Our highest paid executives continued to be given restricted stock that simply vested over time without job performance requirements. Equity pay should have job performance requirements to align with shareholder interest. These executives also were given a so-called long-term incentive of performance shares which were based on short-term results of 2-years. Our highest paid executives received the key to the corporate jet for their personal travel. Because such a perk is not tied to job performance, it is difficult to justify in terms of shareholder value. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Two directors were inside executives, another director was a former executive and two other directors were potentially-conflicted due to related party transactions (RPTs) with entities affiliated with Wal-Mart. Additionally, there are several other related party transactions involving Walton family members and Wal-Mart executives, that raised concerns regarding the effectiveness of our board in representing the interests of us, the minority shareholders. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">In spite of the Walton family controlling 51 % of the vote, four directors received double-digits in negative votes: Lee Scott, Christopher Williams, CEO Michael Duke and Chairman Robson Walton. Please vote to protect shareholder value: </p>

<p style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-weight:bold; font-size:12pt;" align="justify">
<font color="#007DC3">Special Shareowner Meeting Right - Proposal 5 </font></p>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:20pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:28pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:22pt; color: #007DC3; font-weight:bold">
Walmart&rsquo;s Statement in Opposition to Proposal No.&nbsp;5 </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">The Board believes that adoption of this proposal would not be in the best interests of our company or its shareholders. Consistent with Delaware corporate law, our Bylaws provide that a special meeting of shareholders may be called by a majority of the Board, by the Chairman, and by our President and CEO. This is an appropriate corporate governance provision for a public company of our size because it allows our Board, according to its fiduciary obligations, to exercise its business judgment to determine when it is in the best interests of shareholders to convene a special meeting. Permitting shareholders with as little as ten&nbsp;percent of the outstanding shares, regardless of the holding period, to call special meetings for any reason and at any time creates the risk of special meetings being called by a relatively small minority of shareholders focused on narrow or short-term interests rather than the long-term best interests of the company and all of its shareholders. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">We take shareholders&rsquo; meetings very seriously and take steps to provide shareholders with access to our shareholders&rsquo; meetings, including making our shareholders&rsquo; meetings available via webcast. Holding a special meeting of our shareholders at the request of only ten&nbsp;percent of our shareholders would be a costly undertaking, involve substantial planning, and require us to commit significant resources and attention to the legal and logistical elements of such a meeting. For example, we would incur legal, printing, and mailing costs associated with preparing and distributing the disclosure documents required for a special shareholders&rsquo; meeting. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">The Board also believes that the merits of this proposal should be viewed in light of our company&rsquo;s high standards of corporate governance as discussed in this proxy statement. Our company&rsquo;s existing governance policies and practices provide shareholders with access to the Board and members of senior management and offer ample opportunity for shareholders to express their views to management. These governance policies include the annual election of all Board members and a majority voting requirement for the election of directors. The Board has also determined to include an advisory vote on executive compensation at each annual shareholders&rsquo; meeting until the next required vote on the frequency of shareholder votes on executive compensation because the Board believes it is important to receive feedback from shareholders on this important issue annually. In addition, shareholders may submit shareholder proposals, which, if appropriate under the SEC&rsquo;s rules, may be included in our annual proxy statement and voted on at our annual shareholders&rsquo; meeting. Furthermore, the rules governing companies listed on the NYSE and incorporated under Delaware law require us to submit certain matters to a vote of shareholders for approval, such as mergers, large share issuances or similar transactions, and the approval of equity-based compensation plans. </p>

<p style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-weight:bold; font-size:12pt;" align="justify">
<font color="#007DC3">For the above reasons, the Board recommends that the&nbsp;shareholders vote AGAINST this proposal. </font>
</p>

<p style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 3pt; padding-left: 17.2pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;" align="justify"></p>
<p style="margin:0pt; margin-top:14pt; margin-bottom: 14pt; line-height:10pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt;" align="right">
<img src="footer_walmart.jpg" style="margin-bottom:-5pt;">&nbsp;&nbsp;<i>2013 Proxy Statement</i>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;70</p>
<hr>
<p style="page-break-before:always; margin:0pt; margin-bottom: 28pt; line-height:10pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt;">
<a href="#_TOC"><font color="#0000FF">Back to Contents</font></a>
</p>

<a name="_N15E83"></a>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:30pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:28pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:26pt; font-weight:bold">
<font color="#007DC3">Proposal No.&nbsp;6</font>&nbsp;&nbsp;Equity Retention Requirement </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">

<b>RESOLVED:</b> Shareholders of Wal-Mart Stores, Inc., (the &ldquo;Company&rdquo;) urge the Compensation Committee of the Board of Directors (the &ldquo;Committee&rdquo;) to adopt a policy requiring that senior executives retain a significant&nbsp;percentage of shares acquired through equity compensation programs until reaching normal retirement age or terminating employment with the Company. For the purpose of this policy, normal retirement age shall be defined by the Company&rsquo;s qualified retirement plan that has the largest number of plan participants. The shareholders recommend that the Committee adopt a share retention&nbsp;percentage requirement of at least 75&nbsp;percent of net after-tax shares. The policy should prohibit hedging transactions for shares subject to this policy, which are not sales but reduce the risk of loss to the executive. This policy shall supplement any other share ownership requirements that have been established for senior executives, and should be implemented so as not to violate the Company&rsquo;s existing contractual obligations or the terms of any compensation or benefit plan currently in effect. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">

<b>SUPPORTING STATEMENT:</b> Equity based compensation is an important component of senior executive compensation at our Company. While we encourage the use of equity-based compensation for senior executives, we are concerned that our Company&rsquo;s senior executives are generally free to sell shares received from our Company&rsquo;s equity compensation plans. In our opinion, the Company&rsquo;s current share ownership guidelines for its senior executives do not go far enough to ensure that the Company&rsquo;s equity compensation plans continue to build stock ownership by senior executives over the long-term. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">For example, our Company&rsquo;s share ownership guidelines require the Chief Executive Officer (the &ldquo;CEO&rdquo;) to hold an amount of shares equal to five times his salary or approximately 90,664 shares based on current trading prices. In comparison, the CEO currently owns 1.8&nbsp;million shares. In 2011, our Company granted the CEO up to 255,567 performance share awards, assuming maximum performance and 56,793 restricted shares. In other words, even if performance shares are discounted, one year&rsquo;s equity awards are more than half the Company&rsquo;s share ownership guideline for the CEO. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">We believe that requiring senior executives to only hold shares equal to a set target loses effectiveness over time. After satisfying these target holding requirements, senior executives are free to sell all the additional shares they receive in equity compensation. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Our proposal seeks to better link executive compensation with long-term performance by requiring a meaningful share retention ratio for shares received by senior executives from the Company&rsquo;s equity compensation plans. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Requiring senior executives to hold a significant&nbsp;percentage of shares obtained through equity compensation plans until they reach retirement age will better align the interests of executives with the interests of shareholders and the Company. A 2009 report by the Conference Board Task Force on Executive Compensation observed that such hold-through-retirement requirements give executives &ldquo;an ever growing incentive to focus on long-term stock price performance as the equity subject to the policy increases&rdquo; (available&nbsp;at <i>http://&zwnj;www.conference-board.org/pdf_free/ExecCompensation2009.pdf</i>). </p>

<p style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-weight:bold; font-size:12pt;" align="justify">
<font color="#007DC3">We urge shareholders to vote FOR this proposal. </font>
</p>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:20pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:28pt; font-family:Arial; color: #007DC3; font-size:22pt; font-weight:bold">
Walmart&rsquo;s Statement in Opposition to Proposal No.&nbsp;6 </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">We have adopted robust stock ownership guidelines and other governance policies to ensure that our CEO, Executive Officers, and certain other officers are focused on Walmart&rsquo;s long-term success and that their interests are aligned with those of our shareholders. As explained in the CD&amp;A above, Walmart&rsquo;s stock ownership guidelines require that our CEO maintain beneficial ownership of unrestricted Walmart stock equal in market value to five times his current annual base salary and that all of our Executive Officers and certain other officers must maintain beneficial ownership of unrestricted Walmart stock equal in market value to three times his or her current annual base salary. These officers have five years from their appointment to a position covered by our stock ownership guidelines to achieve these levels of ownership. If any covered officer is not in compliance with the guidelines, he or she may not sell or otherwise dispose of more than 50&nbsp;percent of any Walmart Shares that vest pursuant to any equity award during any period for which he or she is not in compliance with the guidelines until such time as he or she is in compliance with the guidelines and such sale would not cause the covered officer to cease to be in compliance with the guidelines. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">As disclosed in the CD&amp;A, each of our NEOs currently subject to the ownership guidelines is in compliance with these guidelines, and in many cases own Walmart stock significantly in excess of the guideline requirements. For example, as disclosed in the CD&amp;A and noted in the proponent&rsquo;s proposal, our CEO owns Shares valued at more than 50&nbsp;times his current base salary. While certain of our executives subject to the guidelines have not yet been in a position covered by the guidelines for five years, each of these individuals is expected to be in compliance with the guidelines at the time he or she reaches the applicable compliance date. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">In addition to the ownership guidelines, the company&rsquo;s Insider Trading Policy restricts the ability of the members of the Board and Executive Officers to engage in speculative transactions involving company stock. As discussed in the CD&amp;A above, the Insider Trading Policy prohibits hedging transactions (such as swaps, collars, and similar financial instruments) that would eliminate or limit the risks and rewards of Walmart stock ownership. Furthermore, members of the Board and Executive Officers may not at any time use Walmart stock as collateral for a margin loan. Before using Walmart stock as collateral for any other borrowing, members of our Board and Executive Officers must have the pledging arrangement pre-approved by Walmart&rsquo;s Corporate Secretary, and any Walmart Shares pledged by a member of the Board or an Executive Officer will not be counted when determining whether the member of the Board or Executive Officer is in compliance with the stock ownership guidelines. Additionally, the Insider Trading Policy prohibits short selling, buying or selling options, puts or calls, whether exchange-traded or otherwise, or engaging in any other transaction in derivative securities that reflects speculation about the price of our stock or that may place the financial interests of the members of the Board and Executive Officers against the financial interests of our company. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Moreover, we believe the CNGC is the governing body best suited to formulate the company&rsquo;s executive compensation policies. As described in the CD&amp;A, the CNGC has designed our executive compensation program so that long-term equity awards are generally the largest portion of our executives&rsquo; annual compensation packages. The long-term equity awards are allocated 75&nbsp;percent in the form of performance shares, which vest if the company meets pre-defined performance goals over a three-year period provided the executive remains employed by our company, and 25&nbsp;percent in the form of restricted stock, which vests on the third anniversary of the grant date provided the executive </p>

<p style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 3pt; padding-left: 17.2pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;" align="justify"></p>
<p style="margin:0pt; margin-top:14pt; margin-bottom: 14pt; line-height:10pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt;" align="right">
<img src="footer_walmart.jpg" style="margin-bottom:-5pt;">&nbsp;&nbsp;<i>2013 Proxy Statement</i>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;71</p>
<hr>
<p style="page-break-before:always; margin:0pt; margin-bottom: 28pt; line-height:10pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt;">
<a href="#_TOC"><font color="#0000FF">Back to Contents</font></a>
</p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">remains employed by our company. These awards are designed to help align the interests of our executives with the interests of our shareholders and also serve as a retention tool for our company&rsquo;s executives. A policy that would require senior executives to hold 75&nbsp;percent of their equity awards until reaching normal retirement age would put our company at a competitive disadvantage for recruiting and retaining top talent and is not a common practice among our company&rsquo;s peer groups. In addition, this policy would restrict the ability of our executives to diversify their investment portfolios and could motivate executives to leave Walmart earlier than they otherwise would have so they could realize the value of their equity compensation. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">For the foregoing reasons, we believe this proposal is unnecessary and would provide no benefit to the company or its shareholders. Walmart&rsquo;s existing stock ownership guidelines and other governance policies effectively facilitate significant stock ownership by Walmart executives and adopting the proposal would not be in the best interests of Walmart&rsquo;s shareholders. </p>

<p style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-weight:bold; font-size:12pt;" align="justify">
<font color="#007DC3">For the above reasons, the Board recommends that the&nbsp;shareholders vote AGAINST this proposal. </font>
</p>

<a name="_N15EB0"></a>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:30pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:28pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:26pt; font-weight:bold">
<font color="#007DC3">Proposal No.&nbsp;7</font>&nbsp;&nbsp;Independent Chairman </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">

<b>RESOLVED:</b> The stockholders of Wal-Mart Stores,&nbsp;Inc. (the &ldquo;Company&rdquo;) ask the board of directors to adopt a policy that, whenever possible, the board chairman should be a director who has not previously served as an executive officer of the Company and who is &ldquo;independent&rdquo; of management. For these purposes, a director shall not be considered &ldquo;independent&rdquo; if, during the last three years, he or she&mdash; </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">was, or was affiliated with a company that was, an advisor or consultant to the Company, or a significant customer or supplier of the Company; </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">was employed by or had a personal service contract(s) with the Company or its senior management; </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">was affiliated with a company or non-profit entity that received the greater of $2&nbsp;million or 2% of its gross annual revenues from the Company; </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">had a business relationship with the Company that the Company had to disclose under the Securities and Exchange Commission regulations; </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">has been employed by a public company at which an executive officer of the Company serves as a director; </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">had a relationship of the sort described above with any affiliate of the Company; and </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">was a spouse, parent, child, sibling or in-law of any person described above. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">The policy should be implemented without violating any contractual obligation and should specify how to select an independent chairman if a current chairman ceases to be independent between annual shareholder meetings. Compliance with the policy may be excused if no independent director is available and willing to be chairman. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify"><u>SUPPORTING STATEMENT</u>

</p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">The Board of Directors, led by its chairman, is responsible for protecting shareholders&rsquo; long-term interests by providing independent oversight of management, including the Chief Executive Officer (&ldquo;CEO&rdquo;), in directing the corporation&rsquo;s affairs. In our view, this oversight can be diminished when the chairman is not independent. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">We believe that an independent Chairman who sets agendas, priorities and procedures for the board can enhance its oversight and accountability of management and help ensure the objective functioning of an effective board. We view the alternative of having a lead outside director, even one with a robust set of duties, as adequate only in exceptional circumstances fully disclosed by the board. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Recent bribery and corruption issues at the company&rsquo;s Mexican subsidiary highlight the need for enhanced oversight of Wal-Mart&rsquo;s corporate culture and behaviour. A board led by an independent chairman is best positioned to drive such change. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Several respected institutions recommend such separation. CalPERS&rsquo; Corporate Core Principles and Guidelines state that &ldquo;the independence of a majority of the Board is not enough&rdquo;; &ldquo;the leadership of the board must embrace independence, and it must ultimately change the way in which directors interact with management.&rdquo; In 2009 Yale School of Management&rsquo;s Millstein Center issued a report, endorsed by a number of investors and directors, that recommended splitting the two positions as the default provision for U.S. companies. </p>

<p style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-weight:bold; font-size:12pt;" align="justify">
<font color="#007DC3">We urge you to vote FOR this proposal. </font>
</p>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:20pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:28pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:22pt; font-weight:bold">


<font color="#007DC3">Walmart&rsquo;s Statement in Opposition to Proposal No.&nbsp;</font>

<font color="#007DC3">7</font>

</p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Walmart has always strived to maintain high corporate governance standards. In keeping with this goal, the Board has separated the roles of Chairman and CEO since 1988. As stated in our Corporate Governance Guidelines, the Board has a policy of separating the roles of Chairman and CEO. As described under the heading &ldquo;Board Leadership Structure&rdquo; above, we believe this separation of roles allows our CEO to focus on managing Walmart&rsquo;s complex daily operations. We also believe that having a separate Chairman focused on oversight and governance matters allows the Board to more effectively perform its risk oversight role. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">In addition, we have a number of other key corporate governance measures that ensure our Board acts independently of management: </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">

<i>Independent presiding director.</i> Since 2004, our Board has appointed an independent presiding director over executive sessions of our Non-Management Directors and Independent Directors. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">

<i>Majority independent Board.</i> Currently 12 of the 17&nbsp;members of our Board are independent, and 15 of the 17&nbsp;Board members are Non-Management Directors. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">

<i>Fully independent key Board committees</i>. All members of the Audit Committee and Compensation, Nominating and Governance Committee are independent. The chairs of these committees are heavily engaged in establishing agendas for committee meetings. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">

<i>Annual Board and Board committee self-assessments.</i> As required by our Corporate Governance Guidelines, the Board and each of the Board committees evaluate their organization and processes each year to ensure that the Board and Board committees are functioning effectively. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Our Chairman has more than 40&nbsp;years of experience with Walmart, and is well positioned to provide our CEO with guidance, advice, and counsel regarding Walmart&rsquo;s business, operations, and strategy. Moreover, our Chairman&rsquo;s significant </p>

<p style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 3pt; padding-left: 17.2pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;" align="justify"></p>
<p style="margin:0pt; margin-top:14pt; margin-bottom: 14pt; line-height:10pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt;" align="right">
<img src="footer_walmart.jpg" style="margin-bottom:-5pt;">&nbsp;&nbsp;<i>2013 Proxy Statement</i>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;72</p>
<hr>
<p style="page-break-before:always; margin:0pt; margin-bottom: 28pt; line-height:10pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt;">
<a href="#_TOC"><font color="#0000FF">Back to Contents</font></a>
</p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">ownership stake in our company provides unparalleled alignment with the interests of his fellow shareholders. Our shareholders have recognized the effectiveness of our current Board leadership structure by re-electing our Chairman and other Board members by wide margins each year. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">We note that the proponent, in its supporting statement, cites a 2009 report by the Yale School of Management&rsquo;s Millstein Center for Corporate Governance and Performance (Chairing the Board: The Case for Independent Leadership in Corporate North America, available at <i>http://millstein.som.yale.edu/sites/millstein.som.yale.edu/files/2009%2003%2030%20Chairing%20The%20Board%20final.pdf</i> (the &ldquo;Millstein Report&rdquo;)). Far from supporting this proposal, a significant portion of the Millstein Report focuses on the value of separating the roles of Chair and CEO, a structure that Walmart already has in place. Moreover, the Millstein Report recognizes that there is no &ldquo;one size fits all&rdquo; approach to Board leadership: </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">&ldquo;The vast majority of advocates of the separation [of the roles of Chair and CEO] . . . recognizes that specific company conditions may warrant the combination under exceptional circumstances. In these cases, most would agree that companies should explain to shareowners why such an alternative model best serves the long-term interests of the corporation and its investors. For example, a situation in which a company may choose to explain rather than comply with separating the roles may include a family controlled enterprise in which the CEO and Chair is the majority shareowner.&rdquo; (<i>Millstein Report,</i> at 20). </p>

<p style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-weight:bold; font-size:12pt;" align="justify">
<font color="#007DC3">For the above reasons, the Board recommends that the&nbsp;shareholders vote AGAINST this proposal. </font>
</p>

<a name="_N15F01"></a>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:30pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:28pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:26pt; font-weight:bold">
<font color="#007DC3">Proposal No.&nbsp;8</font>&nbsp;&nbsp;Request for Annual Report on Recoupment of Executive Pay </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">

<b>RESOLVED</b>, that shareholders of Wal-Mart Stores, Inc. (&ldquo;Walmart&rdquo;) urge the board of directors (the &ldquo;Board&rdquo;) to adopt a policy (the &ldquo;Policy&rdquo;) that Walmart will disclose annually whether Walmart, in the previous fiscal year, recouped any incentive or stock compensation from any senior executive or caused a senior executive to forfeit an outstanding incentive or stock compensation award, in each case as a result of a determination that the senior executive breached a company policy or engaged in conduct inimical to the interests of or detrimental to Walmart. For purposes of this proposal, &ldquo;senior executive&rdquo; includes a former senior executive. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">The Policy should provide that the general circumstances of the recoupment or forfeiture will be described. The Policy should also provide that if no recoupment or forfeiture of the kind described above occurred in the previous fiscal year, a statement to that effect will be included in the report. The disclosure made under the Policy is intended to supplement, not supplant, any disclosure of recoupment or forfeiture required by law or regulation. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">

<b>SUPPORTING STATEMENT </b>

</p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">As long-term shareholders, we believe that compensation policies should promote sustainable value creation. We agree with former GE general counsel Ben Heineman Jr. that recoupment policies with business-related misconduct triggers are &ldquo;a powerful mechanism for holding senior leadership accountable to the fundamental mission of the corporation: proper risk taking balanced with proper risk management and the robust fusion of high performance with high integrity.&rdquo; (<i>http://blogs.law.harvard.edu/corpgov/2010/08/13/making-sense-out-of-clawbacks/</i>)<i>.</i>

</p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Walmart has mechanisms in place to recoup certain incentive compensation upon a finding of unethical conduct. Walmart&rsquo;s Management Incentive Plan provides for recoupment of incentive compensation paid in the previous 12&nbsp;months if the Compensation, Nominating and Governance Committee (the &ldquo;Committee&rdquo;) determines that the recipient engaged in any act deemed inimical to the best interests of the company or failed to comply with company policies. (Management Incentive Plan, section 4.3(b)) Similarly, the Stock Incentive Plan provides for forfeiture of outstanding awards and repayment of amounts received in respect of certain plan awards, in the event the recipient is found by the Committee to have engaged in conduct detrimental to Walmart&rsquo;s best interests. (Stock Incentive Plan of 2010, section 11.5) Separation agreements with several recently retired senior executives state that Walmart is entitled to suspend and recoup payments made under any agreement with the executive if a failure on the executive&rsquo;s part to abide by Walmart&rsquo;s Statement of Ethics is discovered. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Disclosure of the application of these recoupment/forfeiture provisions to senior executives would inform Walmart&rsquo;s shareholders whether the provisions have been applied and allow shareholders to hold members of the Committee accountable for their administration of the provisions. For example, disclosure would enable shareholders to determine whether Walmart recouped compensation from any current or former senior executive as a result of Foreign Corrupt Practices Act violations currently being investigated in Mexico, China, India and Brazil. <i>(http://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/16/business/wal-mart-expands-foreign-bribery-investigation.html?pagewanted=all</i>). </p>

<p style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-weight:bold; font-size:12pt;" align="justify">
<font color="#007DC3">We urge shareholders to vote FOR this proposal. </font>
</p>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:20pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:28pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:22pt; font-weight:bold">


<font color="#007DC3">Walmart&rsquo;s Statement in Opposition to Proposal No.&nbsp;</font>

<font color="#007DC3">8</font>

</p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">The Board recommends that shareholders vote against this proposal because existing SEC disclosure rules already require sufficient disclosures regarding Walmart&rsquo;s comprehensive recoupment policies and practices. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">The Board and our management believe that compensation policies should promote sustainable value creation. That is why we include in our compensation plans, offer letters, and other agreements numerous terms and conditions that give us broad rights to recoup or not to pay compensation otherwise payable to Associates or former Associates who have engaged in misconduct. We believe that these recoupment rights are broader than those provided to the boards and management of many companies and reflect Walmart&rsquo;s strong commitment to ethics and integrity. Walmart&rsquo;s broad existing recoupment rights include the following: </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Our cash incentive plan states that a participant must have complied with Walmart&rsquo;s policies, including our Statement of Ethics, at all times in order to be eligible to receive an incentive payment. Moreover, a participant must repay an incentive award upon demand if the CNGC determines within twelve months of its payment that prior to the award&rsquo;s payment the participant violated any of our policies or otherwise committed acts inimical to the best interests of our company. </p>

<p style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 3pt; padding-left: 17.2pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;" align="justify"></p>
<p style="margin:0pt; margin-top:14pt; margin-bottom: 14pt; line-height:10pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt;" align="right">
<img src="footer_walmart.jpg" style="margin-bottom:-5pt;">&nbsp;&nbsp;<i>2013 Proxy Statement</i>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;73</p>
<hr>
<p style="page-break-before:always; margin:0pt; margin-bottom: 28pt; line-height:10pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt;">
<a href="#_TOC"><font color="#0000FF">Back to Contents</font></a>
</p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">Our Stock Incentive Plan provides that if the CNGC determines that an Associate has committed any act detrimental to the best interests of our company, he or she will forfeit all unexercised options and unvested Shares of restricted stock and performance shares. </p>

<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: -11pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">&bull;</font>
</p>
<p align="justify" style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 6pt; padding-left: 18pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;">When an Executive Officer leaves Walmart, we generally enter into a separation agreement that states &ldquo;[t]he Associate&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;acknowledges that the Associate has complied with the applicable Statement of Ethics during the Associate&rsquo;s employment. The discovery of a failure to abide by the Statement of Ethics, whenever discovered, shall entitle Walmart to suspend and recoup any payments paid or due under this Agreement or any other agreements between the parties.&rdquo; Our Statement of Ethics, among other directives, forbids all Associates from being dishonest, acting illegally, and having conflicts between the Associate&rsquo;s work and personal affairs. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Walmart and the Board are committed to pursuing recoupment actions against current and former Associates believed to have acted unethically. We already are required by SEC disclosure requirements to disclose in our annual proxy statement when compensation has been recouped, and the amount recouped, from our NEOs. Moreover, where necessary to an understanding of our compensation policies and compensation decisions regarding the NEOs, we already must disclose in our annual proxy statement the reasons for the recoupment and how we determined the amount to be recovered. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">This proposal seeks to require these disclosures with respect to all current and former &ldquo;senior executives,&rdquo; a term that is not defined in the proposal. However, as noted above, the SEC&rsquo;s existing disclosure rules already require Walmart to disclose recoupment from both certain current and former Executive Officers who served during the prior fiscal year, to the extent that such individuals meet the SEC&rsquo;s definition of an NEO. We do not believe that expanding the disclosure requirements to all current and former &ldquo;senior executives&rdquo; is warranted. </p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">In sum, the Board believes this proposal is unnecessary because existing SEC disclosure rules already require sufficient disclosures regarding Walmart&rsquo;s comprehensive recoupment policies and practices. </p>

<p style="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-weight:bold; font-size:12pt;" align="justify">
<font color="#007DC3">For the above reasons, the Board recommends that the&nbsp;shareholders vote AGAINST this proposal. </font>
</p>

<a name="_N15F3A"></a>

<p style="margin-top:30pt; margin-bottom:30pt;padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt; line-height:27pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:26pt;">
<font color="#007DC3">

OTHER MATTERS

</font>
</p>

<p style="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:6pt; padding-left: 8.5pt; text-indent: 0pt; line-height:11pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt;" align="justify">Our company is not aware of any matters that will be considered at the 2013 Annual Shareholders&rsquo; Meeting other than the matters described in this proxy statement. If any other matters are properly brought before the 2013 Annual Shareholders&rsquo; Meeting, the proxy holders will vote the Shares as to which they hold proxies in their discretion.</p>

<p style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 3pt; padding-left: 17.2pt; line-height: 11.5pt; font-family: Arial; font-size: 9pt;" align="justify"></p>
<p style="margin:0pt; margin-top:14pt; margin-bottom: 14pt; line-height:10pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt;" align="right">
<img src="footer_walmart.jpg" style="margin-bottom:-5pt;">&nbsp;&nbsp;<i>2013 Proxy Statement</i>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;74</p>
<hr>
<p style="page-break-before:always; margin:0pt; margin-bottom: 28pt; line-height:10pt; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt;">
